desc.en: Düsseldorf International Airport (airport code DUS) is Europe's 20th busiest airport with almost 19 million passengers annually. Located 6 kilometers north of the city, Düsseldorf Airport is 40 kilometers from Cologne and 230 kilometers from Frankfurt. The airport's GermanRail station connects to the city using S-Bahn 11. Taxis, buses and rentals cars are also available. The airport has three terminals, A, B, and C plus an Executive Terminal for private and corporate aircraft. The Sky Train shuttles passengers between terminals. Over 60 airlines service the airport with 186 non-stop destinations. The airport serves a metropolitan area of 18 million people, the 3rd largest in Europe and 7th in the world.

Spokane International Airport (airport code GEG) is located 6 miles west of downtown Spokane, Washington. Only 26 miles from Coeur d'Alene, Idaho, the airport serves Eastern Washington and Northern Idaho. Hosting over 3 million travelers annually, the airport has a main terminal with Concourses A and B on the west side and Concourse C on the east. Seven commercial airlines provide service to the Pacific Northwest and farther afield to Minneapolis, Minnesota, Denver, Colorado, and Phoenix, Arizona. The Spokane Transit Authority provides bus service between the airport and the downtown Transportation Plaza. Rental cars and shuttles are also available. The airport plans to add another concourse in the near future.

San Antonio International Airport (airport code SAT) is located eight miles north of downtown. The GO Airport Shuttle provides travelers with direct service to downtown hotels every 15 minutes daily. The airport's two terminals, A and B, see over eight million visitors each year. Terminal A was recently renovated while the new Terminal B was finished in 2010. A projected Terminal C is scheduled for construction in the near future. Twelve airlines serve passengers with 31 non-stop destinations across the US and in Mexico. With the Alamo historic site and friendly River Walk, San Antonio is a vacation destination as well as centrally located for businesses in south central Texas.

Miami International Airport (airport code MIA) is the 2nd busiest airport for international traffic in the United States. Located just 6 miles west of downtown Miami and 10 miles from its famous beaches, Miami is a popular destination for vacationers. Operated by the Miami-Dade Aviation Department, Miami International is the US gateway to Latin America and the Caribbean. The airport has three terminals, North, Central and South with both the Central and South terminals handling international travelers. Although public transportation from MIA is spotty, taxis, shuttles and rental cars are easily obtainable. The Miami International Airport Hotel is located inside the airport at Concourse E. The airport has over 80 airlines providing flights to over 150 destinations around the world. The airport is currently being renovated and expanded to more than 7 million square feet, which is scheduled for completion in 2012.

Lambert-St. Louis International Airport (airport code STL) is located approximately 10 miles northwest of downtown St. Louis, Missouri, and is in the Top 50 of busiest US airports with over 12 million passengers each year. The airport has two terminals. Terminal 1 has three concourses, A, B and D and Terminal 2 has Concourse E and serves international travelers. Terminal 1 is undergoing renovations and improvements. Both terminals have a MetroLink rail station with direct trains to downtown St. Louis. Buses, taxis and rental cars are also available. Thirteen commercial airlines provide service to the airport with non-stop service across the US and in Canada, Mexico and the Caribbean.

Ted Stevens Anchorage International Airport (airport code ANC) is located 4 nautical miles southwest of Anchorage, Alaska. With both Federal Express (FedEx) and UPS hubs, Anchorage Airport is the 5th busiest cargo airport in the world and serves over 5 million passengers each year. The airport has two terminals, North and South. Transportation options include rental cars, buses and taxis. Over 15 air carriers provide service to Anchorage with flights to the continental US, Asia and seasonal service to Zurich, Switzerland. Named after a former US Senator, Anchorage Airport is also the world's largest and busiest floatplane base and connects travelers to some of the most remote regions in Alaska.

Abu Dhabi International Airport (airport code AUH) is located in the capital of the United Arab Emirates. The airport has over 40 airlines serving 80 cities in over 45 countries. The airport has three terminals, 1, 2, and 3. Terminal 3, serving Etihad Airways exclusively, opened in 2009 and Terminal 1 just reopened after undergoing extensive renovations, which will allow the airport to serve 12 million passengers each year. Located 32 kilometers from the city center, a variety of public and private coaches, shuttles, taxis, and cars can take visitors into Abu Dhabi, which is located on an island in the Arabian Gulf and connected to the mainland by bridges.

Raleigh-Durham International Airport (airport code RDU) is located about 15 miles west of Raleigh, North Carolina. The airport has two terminals, 1 and 2. Terminal 1 is a hub to both AirTran and Southwest. A brand new Terminal 2 opened in 2011 and handles the majority of airlines and passengers. Ground transportation is provided by a variety of services including public buses and trains, taxis, shuttles and rental cars. The airport serves the area known Research Triangle Park, home to more than 170 global companies such as IBM, Syngenta, Cisco and Credit Suisse.  The surrounding area includes Cary, Durham and Chapel Hill, home to the University of North Carolina.

General Mitchell International Airport (airport code MKE) is located 5 miles south of downtown Milwaukee, Wisconsin. With about 8 million passengers a year, Mitchell Airport is in the Top 30 "Fastest-growing Airports in the World" by Airports Council International. Nine airlines provide non-stop service to 48 cities including international stops in Mexico and Canada.  The airport consists of one terminal with three concourses, Concourse C, Concourse D and Concourse E. International flights arrive at the International Terminal located north of the parking structure. Rental cars, shuttles and buses provide ground transportation. Amtrak's Hiawatha line also stops at the airport. Besides service to downtown Milwaukee, Hiawatha line travels to Chicago's Union Station.

Brussels Airport (airport code BRU) is located 11 kilometers northeast of the capital of Belgium. Brussels is also the headquarters of the European Union and NATO. The Airport City Express provides train service to Brussels's three main stations with departures every 20 minutes. Hosting over 17 million passengers, the airport has one terminal with two concourses, called piers, A and B. The airport has a separate road for cyclists and pedestrians and it includes a special parking space for bicycles. Meeting services at the airport include reception rooms for 2 to 600 people. The 5-star Sheraton Brussels Airport Hotel is only 39 steps from the terminal with 294 soundproof rooms.

Piarco International Airport (airport code POS) is located in Piarco on the Caribbean island of Trinidad and serves the two-island republic of Trinidad and Tobago. The airport is about 25 kilometers east of the capital Port of Spain. Completed in 2001, the airport built a new terminal building to replace the old building that now handles cargo. Nineteen airlines provide service to 27 international destinations for over 2 million travelers each year. Trinidad is the industrial capital with oil, natural gas and steel industries while Tobago is the draw of tourists. Birthplace of the steel drum and calypso music, Trinidad and Tobago are the southernmost islands of the West Indies.

Addis Ababa Bole International Airport (airport code ADD) is located on the southern outskirts of the Ethiopian capital city of Addis Ababa. With more than 3 million passengers per year, Bole Airport is Africa's 3rd busiest airport with flights throughout Africa, Europe and the Middle East. About 3 kilometers from the city center, taxis, hotel shuttles and tour group shuttles are available. The airport has two terminals. Terminal 1 serves domestic and regional air carriers while Terminal 2 serves international flights.  The airport is currently undergoing a complete renovation and expansion with the opening of a third terminal due sometime in 2011. Currently, 15 airlines provide service to the airport.

Antalya International Airport (airport code AYT) is located outside of Antalya, Turkey, and serves as the gateway to the Turkish Riviera. The airport features Terminal 1, serving both domestic and international travelers. Terminal 1 also has the Domestic and CIP terminals. Opened in 2007, Terminal 2 was built to help handle the over 15 million passengers the airport sees each year. About 11 kilometers outside the city center, a variety of transportation options are available including Havas Airport Shuttle, city buses, taxis and rental cars. About 725 kilometers south of Istanbul with several direct flights from London, Antalya is a vacationers' paradise with both modern resorts and ancient ruins.

San Diego International Airport (airport code SAN), called Lindbergh Field by locals, is located 3 miles northwest of downtown San Diego, California. The airport is the nation's busiest single-runway commercial airport with 600 daily flights. The airport has three terminals, 1 and 2 and the Commuter Terminal. The Metropolitan Transit System operates the San Diego Transit Flyer (Bus No. 992) providing direct service between the airport and downtown San Diego and stops at all three terminals. Taxis, shuttles and rental cars are also available. The airport has 22 airlines providing non-stop service throughout the United States including both Maui and Honolulu in Hawaii and non-stop services to Mexico and Canada.

Kuala Lumpur International Airport (airport code KUL) is the 23rd busiest airport in passenger traffic in the world. A Southeast Asian hub with 27 airlines, the airport hosts around 35 million passengers annually. Often referred to as KLIA, the airport has three buildings that make up the terminal complex, the Satellite Building which handles international travelers, the Contact Pier which serves passengers of Malaysia Airlines and the Main Terminal, also called Terminal 1. Located 35 miles south of the Malaysian city of Kaula Lumpur, Express Rail Link has a 28-minute KLIA Express train to the downtown. Buses and taxis are also available. The 5-star Pan Pacific Hotel KLIA is on-site.

Larnaca (or Larnaka) International Airport (airport code LCA) is located on the island of Cyprus in the Mediterranean Sea 75 kilometers south of Turkey, 380 kilometers north of Egypt and 380 kilometers east of Rhodes (Greece). Located 4 kilometers southwest of the city, Larnaca Airport is easily accessed with shuttles, taxis and car rentals providing transportation to the rest of the island. After opening a new terminal 2008, the airport is currently in its second phase of expansion scheduled for completion in 2013 when the airport expects to hand some 9 million passengers each year. A vacation destination for Europeans on holiday, Cyprus offers travelers beautiful beaches and rugged mountains.

Mineta San José International Airport (airport code SJC) is located in the heart of Silicon Valley, 3 miles north from downtown San José, California, and only 45 miles from San Francisco.  The airport has two terminals, Terminal A & International Arrivals and the new Terminal B (June 2010). Serving 8.2 million passengers annually, San José has non-stop service to cities throughout the US, Hawaii and Mexico. In 2010, Terminal B was given LEED Silver certification for sustainable design and construction. http://www.flysanjose.com/
 
Along with regular ground transportation services, travelers can take the free VTA #10 Airport Flyer to the Metro/ N.First St. Light Rail Station or Santa Clara Caltrain Station for access to Bay Area Rapid Transit (BART), Amtrak, and Caltrain.

 
Airlines that service SJC:


Terminal A: American, American Eagle, Continental, Delta, Hawaiian, jetBlue, United, United Express, US Airways and Volaris.

 
Terminal B: Alaska, Horizon, and Southwest

Buffalo Niagara International Airport (airport code BUF) is located 10 miles east of downtown Buffalo, New York and is 26 miles from Niagara Falls near the Canadian border. In fact, Canadians flying to US cities make up 2 million of the almost 4 million passengers the airport sees each year. The airport has one two-level terminal with departures on the upper level and arrivals on the lower level. Close to the New York State Thruway (I-90), rental cars, taxis and limousines are all available. NFTA-Metro buses also provide service with an Airport-Downtown Express shuttle and an Airport-Niagara Falls Express Shuttle. Eight airlines average 110 daily flights with 23 non-stop destinations.

London Luton Airport (airport code LTN) is London's 5th largest passenger airport with almost 9 million passengers each year. The majority of travelers into Luton come from the European mainland on nine air carriers from cities such as Budapest, Hungary, and Geneva, Switzerland. The airport is almost 2 miles from the town of Luton in Bedfordshire, England and is 35 miles from central London. Travel into London is through regular rail service and takes a little as 21 minutes. Taxis, buses and rental cars are also available using the M1 and M25 motorways. The airport has one terminal with two levels, Level 1 for arrivals and Level 2 for departures.

Cape Town International Airport (airport code CPT) is located 20 kilometers from downtown Cape Town in South Africa and is the country's 2nd busiest airport and the third busiest in Africa. Recently updated and expanded for the 2010 FIFA World Cup, Cape Town Airport has a split-level Central Terminal Building with departures located on upper floors and arrivals in lower floors. Passenger transit is conducted from the Transport Plaza and Car Rental Facility located in front of the Central Terminal. Buses, taxis and cars are available here. Both the domestic and international departure areas feature a Premier Lounge, available with fee to any passenger regardless of airline or ticket class.

Sangster International Airport (airport code MBJ) is located 3 miles east of Montego Bay, Jamaica. Not only is the airport a gateway to Jamaica, Sangster is also the hub for many airlines taking passengers all over the Caribbean. The airport has one two-level terminal and plenty of rental cars, taxis or hotel shuttles to get passengers where they need to go. Sangster airport has over 30 airlines serving over 9 million passengers annually with arrivals mainly from the United States, Canada and Europe. Located on the northwest coast of Jamaica, the airport is 101 miles from the capital of Kingston, 65 miles from Ocho Rios and 41 miles from Negril.

John F. Kennedy International Airport (airport code JFK) is the United States' 6th busiest airport and was originally built in 1948 and renamed for the slain American president in December 1963. Operated by the Port Authority of New York & New Jersey, JFK Airport is located in the borough of Queens only 15 miles from midtown Manhattan. JFK has eight operating terminals with 125 gates serving over 70 airlines. After a $1.4 billion redevelopment in 2001, Terminal 4 serves international passengers with the airport's only 24-hour Customs and Border Protection and has the airport's only internal AirTrain station to take passengers to the Long Island Rail Road and New York City subway making for easy access to major corporations and tourist destinations. New York entertainment includes television, music and nine major sports teams. Whether dining at one of 17,000-plus restaurants, strolling around 843-acre Central Park or shopping on fashionable Fifth Avenue, New York City has something for everyone.

Rick Husband Amarillo International Airport (airport code AMA) is located just 6 miles east of downtown Amarillo, Texas, in the north Texas panhandle. The airport was renamed in 2003 after Amarillo native and NASA astronaut Richard Husband, who died aboard the Space Shuttle Columbia earlier that year. The airport has one Main Terminal and is nearing completion of a major airport renovation project, which will include a new concourse, an automated baggage handling system and an upgrade to the building's HVAC systems. Four air carriers serve the airport:  American Eagle, Continental Express, Southwest and United. Just 2 miles north of I-40, buses, taxis and rental cars are available for transport.

Shanghai Pudong International Airport (airport code PVG) opened in 1999 and is already the world's 20th busiest airport and China's 3rd busiest, hosting over 40 million passengers annually. The airport is a hub for both Shanghai Airlines and China Eastern Airlines. The passenger complex consists of two terminals, T1 and T2, with a third terminal expected to open in 2015. There are two hotels on-site, the Ramada Pudong Airport Hotel and the JinjiangInn Pudong Airport Hotel. Located 30 kilometers southeast of the city center, the airport is connected to the city by the Metro Line Subway system and the Shanghai Maglev High-speed Train, which takes less than eight minutes.

desc.en: Changi Airport in Singapore (airport code SIN) is the world's 17th busiest airport serving 100 international airlines to more than 60 countries. Built just 30 years ago, Changi has come a long way from just one terminal in 1988 to four terminals today. Terminal 1 is currently undergoing renovations to be completed in 2012. Terminal 2 was renovated in 2006 and Terminal 3 opened in 2008 and is connected to the rest of the airport via Skytrain. The Budget Terminal serves low-cost carriers in Asia. The entire airport handles over 19 million passengers every year. Changi has received the World's Best Airport award from Ultratravel Magazine the last four years.

Cancun Airport International (airport code CUN) is one of the busiest airports in the Caribbean and the 2nd busiest in Mexico with over 12 million visitors each year. The airport has two terminal buildings, the Main Terminal, for domestic and international flights from major airlines, and the FBO Terminal serving charted flights and private planes. Located 22 kilometers from downtown on the Cancun-Chetumal Highway, airport transfers can be arranged through the airport's website using taxis, buses, hotel shuttles and private cars. Serving the Mayan Riviera resort region, Cancun Airport is 45 minutes from Playa del Carmen, 90 minutes from Tulum and 2 hours from the ancient ruins of Chichen Itza.

Bandaranaike International Airport (airport code CMB) at Katunayake, Sri Lanka, is 30 kilometers north of the island nation's capital of Colombo. Twenty-four airlines currently serve the airport's over 4 million annual passengers. Taxis, buses and rental cars are available for transportation. The airport has three passenger terminals. Terminal 1 is for international flights, Terminal 2 is also international and undergoing expansion, and the new Terminal 3 for domestic flights is expected to open March 2012. The airport's new Silk Route lounge recently opened expediting the customs process for Commercially Important Passengers. In 2011, Sri Lanka was a co-host for the 2011 ICC Cricket World Cup along with India and Bangladesh.

Mohammed V International Airport (airport code CMN) is located in Morocco about 30 kilometers southeast of Casablanca. The busiest airport in Morocco has almost 7.25 million passengers annually and is named after the late Sultan Mohammed V. The airport has three terminals, Terminals 1 and 3 for international passengers and Terminal 2 and is served by trains, taxies and rental cars. Each week the airport has 182 flights to Paris, 17 flights to New York, and 14 flights to Dubai and Frankfurt. The airport features a hotel inside Terminal 2 for transiting passengers. Aeropole Casablanca is a 700-acre business park adjoining the airport featuring such companies as Boeing and Labinal.

Austin Straubel International Airport (airport code GRB) is located 7 miles southwest of downtown Green Bay, Wisconsin. As the 3rd largest airport in Wisconsin, Straubel is served by five airlines with direct service to seven cities, including Chicago, Illinois, Cleveland, Ohio, Detroit, Michigan and Minneapolis/St. Paul, Minnesota. Flights to Denver, Colorado, are seasonal. Connecting northeast Wisconsin and Michigan's Upper Peninsula, Straubel Airport hosts almost a half million passengers each year. Rental cars, taxis and shuttle provide transport into Green Bay. The airport has two concourses, A and B, with six gates each.  On NFL game days, Green Bay Metro provides free bus service between the airport and Lambeau Field.

Seattle-Tacoma International Airport (airport code SEA) is more commonly referred to as Sea-Tac and is the gateway to the Pacific Northwest of the United States. Sea-Tac is 17th busiest airport in the US serving over 31.5 million passengers. The airport has a Central Terminal with four branching concourses, A through D. There are also two Satellite Terminals, North and South. The airport has over 20 airlines and includes international non-stop flights to cities such as Beijing, China, Calgary, Canada, Dubai, UAE, and Seoul, South Korea. Located between the cities of Seattle and Tacoma, the Light Rail Link's SeaTac Airport Station is connected to the fourth floor of the Airport Garage.

Ronald Reagan National Airport (airport code DCA) is located 3 miles south of the capital of the United States, Washington DC. Renamed in 1998 for the former US president, National Airport has three terminals, A, B and C.  Because it is so close to the nation's capital, National Airport only provides US immigration and customs service for corporate jets only. The only international flights allowed are from the Bahamas and Bermuda, and major Canadian airports. All other international traffic goes to Dulles Airport or north to Baltimore-Washington Airport. The airport handles over 18 million passengers each year and is connected directly with DC's Metrorail system for transport into the capital.

Indianapolis International Airport (airport code IND) is located 7 miles southwest of Indianapolis, Indiana's central business district. As a second US hub for Federal Express (FedEx), Indianapolis is the national's 8th largest cargo carrier and is 22nd in cargo in the world. Hosting over 7 million passengers each year, Indianapolis Airport has 140 daily departures to 34 non-stop destinations throughout the US along with Canada and Mexico. The airport has one terminal with two concourses, A and B. Downtown Indianapolis is just 16 minutes away on I-70 and has rental car and taxi service available along with IndyGo's Green Line Express, which has non-stop service between the airport and downtown.

Perth Airport (airport code PER) is located about 12 kilometers northeast of the city of Perth in Western Australia on the edge of the Indian Ocean. The airport has three terminals. Terminal 1 hosts International travelers. Terminal 2 is the domestic terminal served by Qantas Airlines and Terminal 3, also domestic, is adjacent to Terminal 2. A courtesy bus provides transport between the terminals. The airport also has several smaller terminals for charter and regional service. Transportation to and from the airport is covered by shuttles, buses, taxis and rental cars. The 4th busiest airport in Australia, Perth serves a strategic location for travel to Asia, the Middle East, and South Africa.

Piedmont Triad International Airport (airport code GSO) is located just west of Greensboro, North Carolina. Serving the metropolitan areas of Greensboro, High Point and Winston-Salem, Piedmont is the 3rd busiest airport in North Carolina. With over 800,000 passengers a year, Piedmont offers 10 daily non-stop destinations on eight different airlines and is only one-stop away from destinations all over the globe. The airport has one terminal with two concourses, North and South. The Piedmont Authority for Regional Transportation provides buses, vans and carpools while taxis, hotel shuttles, and rental cars are also available. Federal Express (FedEx) has recently expanded their facility at Piedmont establishing the airport as their Mid-Atlantic hub.

Qabala International Airport (Qəbələ Beynəlxalq Aeroport) (IATA: GBB, ICAO: UBBQ) is an airport serving Qabala[1] (also known as Qəbələ or Gabala), the capital of the Gabala district (rayon) in Azerbaijan. The airport was officially opened by President Ilham Aliyev on 17 November 2011.[3]

Ottawa International Airport (airport code YOW) is about six miles south of the city and is Canada's 6th busiest airport serving over 4.5 million passengers. The airport offers non-stop service to 50 domestic and international destinations. The Passenger Terminal Building, opened in 2003, has three levels including an observation area on Level 3. There are six meeting facilities on-site including the Hunt Club Executive Boardroom that seats 20 with built-in projector. In 2010 Ottawa received several awards including Airport Council International's Service Quality award as the No. 1 airport serving 2-5 million passengers. As a way to give back to the community, Ottawa Airport provides grants through Project Clear Skies.

Sharm el Sheikh International Airport (airport code SSH) serves the resort communities of Hadaba and Naama Bay along the Red Sea. Sharm el Sheikh is Egypt's 2nd busiest airport after Cairo and serves almost 10 million passengers on 13 air carriers each year. The airport has two terminals, Terminal 1, completed in 2007, and Terminal 2. Terminal 3 and a new runway are scheduled to open in 2012. Travel to and from the city takes about 20 minutes by public minibus or prepaid taxi. Originally called Ophira International Airport when it was under Israeli occupation, the area was returned to Egypt as part of the Camp David Accords in 1982.

Dublin Airport (airport code DUB) or Aerfort Bhaile Àtha Cliath in Irish is 11 kilometers north of the center of Dublin, Ireland. AirCoach operates a 24-hour shuttle bus service to the city. Public buses, taxis and rental cars are also available. Featuring two terminals, Terminal 1 is home to all Ryanair flights and European air carriers. Terminal 2 is home to Aer Lingus and mostly US airlines and operates a special US Customs & Border Protection facility inside the terminal, one of only two such facilities outside North America. Among the 10 busiest airports in Europe, Dublin Airport averages 60,000 passengers per day and over 18.5 million passengers per year.

Omaha Eppley Airfield (airport code OMA) serves the Omaha, Nebraska, and Council Bluffs, Iowa, metropolitan area providing air transportation to over 4.2 million passengers each year. Located four miles northeast of downtown Omaha, Eppley Airfield has six airlines with non-stop service to 21 destinations including Minneapolis, Las Vegas, Dallas, New York and Atlanta. The terminal building is divided into North and South and has two Concourses, A and B.  Ground transportation is provided by rental cars, taxis and shuttles, including shuttle service to nearby Lincoln, Sioux City, Iowa and Sioux Falls, South Dakota. Omaha is home to five Fortune 500 companies, the College World Series and the Henry Doorly Zoo.

Port Columbus International Airport (airport code CMH) is located 6 miles east of downtown Columbus, Ohio. Gateway to central Ohio, Columbus Airport has 151 non-stop flights to 34 airports on 15 airlines and over 6 million passengers per year. There are 17 daily flights to Chicago, Illinois, and 20 flights to New York City. The airport has three terminals, Concourse A, Concourse B and Concourse C. The city is accessible by rental car, bus, and taxi via I-670. Two transportation companies, Arch Transportation and Dublin Express provide direct shuttles (with or without reservations) to downtown every 20 minutes. Direct bus service (Route 52) is also provided to Ohio State University.

Orlando International Airport (airport code MCO) is the nation's 13th busiest airport and 26th in the world in passenger traffic. With 43 airlines providing non-stop service to 89 US destinations and 27 international destinations, Orlando Airport is the gateway to the variety of resorts and amusement parks that make up Central Florida. The airport has one central terminal building linked to four airside satellite terminals connected by an automated people mover system. The AAA four diamond Hyatt Regency Airport Hotel is attached directly to the airport. Located 25 miles east of Walt Disney World and 20 miles south of downtown, a variety of shuttle services and rental cars are available.

Newport News/Williamsburg International Airport (airport code PHF) is located 9 miles northwest of downtown Newport News, Virginia. Originally named Patrick Henry Field (PHF), it was renamed in 1990 to better reflect the metropolitan region the airport serves. That area includes the 35th largest population area in the US and the Virginia cities of Hampton, Virginia Beach, Norfolk, Richmond and Suffolk. Hosting over 1 million travelers each year, the airport consists of a main terminal with two concourses, A and B. Five airlines provide service to the airport. Near I-64, which links the airport to the Virginia Chesapeake region, rental cars, taxis and private car services are available for transport.

Prague Ruzyne International Airport (airport code PRG) is located about 10 kilometers west of downtown Prague in the Czech Republic in the suburb of Ruzyne. The nation's largest airport handles between 11 and 12 million passenger each year. The airport has two passenger terminals, North 1 and North 2 (Severin 1 and Severin 2). North 1 handles travelers from outside the European Union including flights from the US and the UK. North 2 handles flights within the EU such as France, Germany, Italy and Switzerland. Taxis, buses and rental cars are available as well. Prague Airport was named "Best Airport in Central and Eastern Europe" by Skytrax in 2005.

Tampa International Airport (airport code TPA) is located 5 miles northwest of downtown Tampa, Florida, and is the gateway to the Tampa Bay Area of Tampa, St. Petersburg and Clearwater. The 30th busiest airport in North America, Tampa sees over 16.5 million travelers each year. The airport consists of a landside/airside terminal with four airside satellites labeled A, C, E and F. Fifteen airlines serve the airport with flights throughout the US and into Canada, Mexico, Europe and the Caribbean. In 2011, the airport began service to Cuba and March 2012 Edelweiss Air will offer non-stop flights to Zurich, Switzerland. For transport, taxis, SuperShuttle, and rental cars are available.

Paphos (or Pafos) International Airport (airport code PFO) is located 6.5 kilometers southeast of the city of Paphos on the island of Cyprus in the eastern Mediterranean Sea. Refurbished in 2008, the airport's main terminal handles about 2 million passengers annually. Airport shuttles and taxis are most commonly used for transport and rental cars are also available. A new airport highway is planned to cut down on traffic congestion. Paphos Airport has over 30 air carriers linking the island to Europe, Asia, Africa and the Middle East. Referred to as the "Island of Aphrodite," Cyprus is a sunny getaway featuring ancient ruins, rugged mountains and inviting beaches along the coastline.

desc.en: Incheon International Airport (airport code ICN) opened in 2001 and is the 3rd largest terminal in size in the world handling 33 million passengers each year. Incheon Airport has one Main Terminal and connects to Concourse A by two underground passageways. Fifty-two kilometers west of the capital of Seoul, South Korea, the airport is on Yeongjong Island and connected to downtown by city buses, taxis and limousines. Although there is no direct rail service, buses can take travelers to nearby subways stations for connections to the city. The Cultural Museum of Korea is located in the Transfer Lounge (4F) and showcases a collection of relics covering 5,000 years of history.

Indira Gandhi International Airport (airport code DEL) is the 30th busiest by passengers and 8th largest in size in the world, serving over 16.5 million people annually. It has two terminals, Terminal 1 for domestic travelers and the recently built Terminal 3 for international travelers. Located 22 kilometers from Delhi, travelers can use the Delhi Airport Metro Express train line from Terminal 3 or take a bus or taxi on the 8-lane Delhi Gurgaon Expressway to get to downtown. The airport provides play areas for families along with complementary strollers for small travelers in Terminal 1D. The Eaton Smart Transit Hotel is located on the fifth floor of Terminal 3.

Kazantzakis Heraklion International Airport (airport code HER) is located 5 kilometers east of the city of Heraklion on the Greek Isle of Crete in the Mediterranean Sea.  The airport is the 2nd busiest in Greece after Athens International Airport with service to 5 million annual passengers using over 50 airlines. The local bus stop is a few minutes' walk from the terminal building. Taxis, hotel shuttles and rental cars are also available. The airport is named for the famed Cretan writer, Nikos Kazantzakis, who wrote Zorba the Greek. The city has several spellings including Heraclion, Irakion and Iraclion, so make sure all baggage tags have airport code HER for verification.

Halifax Stanfield International Airport (airport code YHZ) is located in Enfield, Nova Scotia, Canada, and serves the entire Nova Scotia peninsula. The 7th busiest airport in Canada, Halifax Airport sees over 3.5 million annual passengers. The airport features a three-level terminal with 31 gates. With its unique Atlantic Ocean position, 18 airlines are able to provide Halifax Airport non-stop flights throughout Canada and the eastern US, as well as Iceland, Europe and the Caribbean. Located 35 kilometers from Halifax center, car rentals, Airporter shuttles and taxis are available to transport travelers to and from the airport. The airport has developed a performing arts program featuring vocalists, musicians, dancers and more.

Jomo Kenyatta International Airport (airport code NBO) is located 18 kilometers east of the capital of Nairobi, Kenya. The largest airport in East and Central Africa is served by 49 airlines with direct flights to Europe, the Middle East, the Far East and the African Continent. The terminal building consists of three areas:  Unit I is international departures, Unit II is also international departures, and Unit III serves domestic departures and arrivals. The airport hosts over 5 million passengers each year. Taxis and car rentals are available for transport to and from the airport. The airport is currently undergoing expansion to double its capacity along with a planned rail link.

Heathrow Airport in London (airport code LHR) is Europe's busiest airport and 2nd busiest in the world. Only 24 kilometers from downtown London, Heathrow is connected to the city by the Heathrow Express, a rail line that takes passengers directly to and from Paddington Station in only 15 minutes. Heathrow has four terminals with Terminal 1 serving international customers and those traveling from other parts of the UK and Ireland. In 2011, all terminals were connected by a series of battery-operated Personal Transit Pods that carry passengers and luggage around the airport faster than buses while using less energy. Heathrow works with 56 airlines that fly to over 80 countries. From professional services to historic sights, London is a major international destination and on July 25, 2012, London will host the world's best athletes at the Games of the XXX Olympiad, the third time the city has hosted the games.

Chicago O'Hare International Airport (airport code ORD), the second busiest airport in the US and the world's 4th busiest, is just 20 miles from downtown Chicago with convenient connections by train, bus or car. Home to the tallest building in the Western Hemisphere (The Willis Tower), Chicago has 2.6 million residents and is the gateway to the third largest metropolitan area in the US covering three states-Illinois, Wisconsin and Indiana. From the largest exhibition space in North America (2.2 million SF at McCormick Place Convention Center) to its 26 miles of Lake Michigan shoreline, Chicago has everything for the business or pleasure traveler. Chicago is also corporate headquarters to United Airlines where O'Hare is its major hub. The airport has four terminals with three serving both domestic and international flights (departures only) and one terminal serving international flights only. The Hilton Chicago O'Hare Hotel is directly connected to the airport.

Bucharest Henri Coanda International Airport (airport code OTP) is located 16.5 kilometers northwest of the capital of Bucharest, Romania. Recently renamed after Romanian flight pioneer Henri Coanda, the airport is also known as Otopeni for the town it is located in. While currently under construction, the airport consists of a single terminal divided into two areas, the Departures Hall and the Arrivals Hall. Plans are underway for an additional terminal to be built as well. Over 30 airlines provide transport to almost 5 million passengers each year. The 783 Express Line bus connects the airport with the city center. Taxi, rental cars and some hotel shuttles are also available.

Portland International Airport (airport code PDX) is Oregon's largest commercial airport welcoming over 13 million people a year. The airport has nonstop international service to Amsterdam and Tokyo as well as to many other domesitic locations across the country.  The airport is located just 12 miles outside of downtown Portland and is easily accessible by the MAX Red Line light rail service. PDX prides itself on its top rating in customer service as well as on on-time performance. PDX won the FlightStats On-time Performance award among Major North American Airports with an on-time percentage of 86.02%

Suvarnabhumi International Airport (airport code BKK) in Bangkok, Thailand, is located 30 kilometers east of Bangkok in Racha Thewa in the district of Samut Prakan. Opened in 2006, it is already 6th busiest airport in Asia and 13th busiest in the world. The name "Suvarnabhumi,' chosen by HM King Bhumibol Adulyadej, means Golden Land, which refers the region of Indochina and includes the counties of Thailand, Cambodia, Laos and Burma. The airport features a main terminal with seven concourses, A through G. The Airport Express Line, opened in 2010, provides direct service from the airport to Bangkok. The 612-room Novotel Suvarnabhumi Airport Hotel is connected by walkway to the airport.

Juan Santamaría International Airport (airport code SJO) is located in 20 kilometers from downtown San Jose, Costa Rica. With over 4 million annual passengers, Juan Santamaría is the 2nd busiest airport in Central America. The airport has a Main Terminal serving international passengers while the Sansa Terminal, named for Sansa Airlines, handles domestic flights. Over 15 airlines serve the airport including non-stop routes from the US and Canada, a 3- to 7-hour flight. A bus route runs between the airport and San Jose and taxis, rental cars and shuttles are also available. The airport has a VIP Lounge for business/first class passengers, but available to anyone for a fee.

Charlotte-Douglas International Airport (airport code CLT) is the 11th busiest passenger airport in the US with over 38 million travelers. Served by 10 different airlines, Charlotte-Douglas has138 non-stop destinations including international locations in Mexico, Ireland, Germany, Jamaica and Brazil. There is one terminal with five concourses, A through E. The airport is currently renovating the baggage claim area to be finished before 2012. The largest metropolitan area in North Carolina, Charlotte is the second largest banking center in the US, home to Bank of America and Wells Fargo. Charlotte is also home to professional sports teams Carolina Panthers of the NFL and the Charlotte Bobcats of the NBA.

Gran Canaria Airport (airport code LPA) is located on the east coast of Gran Carania Island in the Canary Islands of Spain. The airport is 18 kilometers from the island's capital, Las Palmas de Gran Canaria and easily accessible by taxi, bus or rental car. The airport has over 9 million visitors annually and is currently undergoing an extension of the airport's terminal to increase capacity. Gran Canaria is 3rd largest of the Canary Islands and the most populous. Not only is it the reason millions of tourists visit each year, the island's temperate climate is also why the airport sees fewer closures or other issues due to inclement weather.

desc.en: Cairo International Airport (airport code CAI) in Egypt is the 2nd busiest airport in Africa with over 16 million passengers. The airport has four terminals. Terminal 1 handles both domestic and international travelers. Terminal 3 and the Seasonal Terminal opened in 2008 and 2011 respectively. The Seasonal Terminal was built to help ease congestion during the holy pilgrimages of the Hajj. Terminal 2 is closed for renovations until 2015. Located 22 kilometers northeast of the city and only 40 kilometers from the Giza Pyramids, transportation choices include the Cairo Airport Shuttle, taxis, buses and rental cars. The Le Meridien Hotel next to Terminal 3 is scheduled to open in 2012.

Norman Manley International Airport (airport code KIN) is located about 27 kilometers from Kingston, Jamaica, the country's capital and the largest English-speaking city in the Caribbean. The airport has 14 airlines with 130 international flights per week and serves 1.7 million annual travelers, mostly from North America, the United Kingdom and the Caribbean. Official JUTA taxis are available to transport people to and from the airport. The airport's main Air Terminal has recently been expanded and upgraded to efficiently accommodate an ever increasing number of travelers. Once called Palisadoes Airport for its location, Manley Airport is currently undergoing renovations to the Ground Transportation Hall and is expanding the Immigration Hall.

Hong Kong International Airport (airport code HKG) is the world's 10th busiest airport handling over 50 million passengers each year. Over 95 airlines operate flights to more than 160 locations worldwide including 45 destinations in mainland China. Opened in 1998, the airport has two terminals, 1 and 2. About 32 kilometers from the central business district, the Airport Express Line has rail service that links directly to the business center. Buses, taxis, ferries and coaches are also readily available. The Regal Airport Hotel is linked to Terminal 1 by covered walkway. In 2011, Hong Kong Airport was chosen by readers of Condé Nast Traveler magazine as the "World's Best Airport."

Baltimore/Washington Thurgood Marshall International Airport (airport code BWI) is the 23rd busiest airport in the US. Located 10 miles south of downtown Baltimore and 30 miles northeast of Washington DC, the Light Rail connects the airport and Amtrak station with downtown Baltimore. Taxis, shuttles and rental cars are available. The airport consists of one passenger terminal with five concourses, four domestic and one international/swing, labeled A through E. A total of 25 commercial airlines offer 69 non-stop domestic flights and 6 international non-stops, including cities such as Cancun, Mexico, London, UK, and Toronto, Canada. The airport is named for a Baltimore native and former US Supreme Court Justice.

Haneda Tokyo International Airport (airport code HND) is located in Ota, Japan, 14 kilometers south of Tokyo Station. Haneda Airport handles mostly domestic flights to and from Tokyo and has two terminals, 1 and 2. Terminal 1 is nicknamed “Big Bird” and features a rooftop observation deck with open-air cafe.  A new dedicated International Terminal opened in 2010. A free shuttle transports travelers between domestic and international terminals. Trains, taxis, and buses transport travelers into Tokyo. Seven domestic and 18 international airlines provide service to the airport. The airport handles over 64 million passengers per year making it the 2nd busiest airport in Asia and 7th busiest in the world.

Sheremetyevo International Airport (airport code SVO) is located in Khimki, Russia, 29 kilometers northwest of central Moscow. Aeroexpress Train has a 40-minute route to Savylovsky Train Station, however, taxis, rental cars and buses are also readily available. The airport has five terminals, B through F. Terminals C and D are new buildings and Terminal F, originally built for the 1980 Olympics, is currently undergoing refurbishment. Terminal B handles domestic and low-cost air carriers. Terminal C handles charter flights and Terminal D is the hub for Russia's Aeroflot airlines. Terminals E and F are for international travelers. Sheremetyevo is Europe's 18 busiest airport and hosts over 19 million passengers each year

Benito Juarez International Airport (airport code MEX) in Mexico City, Mexico, handles over 24 million passengers each year and is Latin American's 2nd busiest airport. Terminal 2, finished in 2007, and the international section of Terminal 1 handle international travelers. Domestic travelers are accommodated by the rest of Terminal 1. It is the main hub for Mexico's largest airline, Aeromexico, and they are the only airline that flies to Asia from Mexico City. Located 5 kilometers east from central Mexico City, special yellow-coded "Authorized Airport Taxis" are available after exiting the baggage claim area. The Hilton Hotel is located inside Terminal 1 and the NH Hotel is at Terminal 2.

Honolulu International Airport (airport code HNL) on the Hawaiian island of Oahu hosts over 20 million visitors each year. Served by 27 air carriers, the airport has three terminals. The recently renovated Oversees Terminal hosts the majority of travelers both international and from the mainland United States. The Commuter Terminal serves smaller airlines and operates flights to the other islands. The Interisland Terminal serves both Hawaiian and Mokulele Airlines and includes their inter-island, US and international flights. The airport provides free transportation to passengers traveling between terminals. Located 6 miles from downtown Honolulu and only 10 miles from Waikiki, transportation can be arranged through shuttles, buses, taxis and rental cars.

Tan Son Nhat International Airport (airport code SGN) is located in 6 kilometers north of the center of Ho Chi Minh City, Vietnam. The airport is the busiest and largest in the country with over 15.5 million visitors annually. The airport consists of two terminals, Terminal 1 for domestic flights and the newly opened Terminal 2 for international flights. Taxis, buses, car hires and motorcycles provide transport into the city, still called Saigon by locals. Over 40 airlines provide service to the airport with flights throughout Asia and Europe. Flights from North America usually arrive via Singapore, Bangkok or Hong Kong. National carrier Vietnam Airlines provides flights throughout the country.

Boryspil International Airport (airport code KBP) is located 6 kilometers west of Boryspil, Ukraine, and 29 kilometers from the capital of Kiev (Kyiv). The airport has three terminals, B, C and F, opened in 2010, and a new terminal is under construction. One of Europe's fastest growing airports, Terminal D is scheduled to open in 2012 (Terminal A was closed in 2011). Over 20 airlines serve the airport flying to 48 countries. The airport hosts over 6.5 million passengers each year and is easily accessible by car, bus and taxi on Motorway M03. Plans are underway to build a rail link from the airport to Kiev's Central Station by Spring 2012.

José Martí International Airport (airport code HAV) in Havana, Cuba, is only 90 miles south of the Florida Keys. Havana is the largest city in the Caribbean while the island of Cuba is the largest Caribbean island and the 17th largest island in the world. Over 25 air carriers provide service to 4 million passengers each year. The airport has four terminals. Terminal 1 is for domestic flyers, Terminal 2, remodeled in 2010, is for charter flights and Terminal 3 is for international flyers. The fourth terminal is Terminal 5 used by Cuban airlines AeroCaribbean and Aerotaxi. Located 15 kilometers southwest of the city, taxis and rental cars are available.

Ministro Pistarini International Airport (airport code EZE) is located in Ezeiza just 22 kilometers from Buenos Aires, Argentina, and is the 11th busiest airport in South America. The airport has three terminals, A, B and the recently opened Terminal C, that host over 8 million travelers each year. Taxis, buses and rental cars are available. Although an overnight flight from most US destinations (up to 11 hours), the 1- to 3-hour overall time difference means less jet lag involved for US passengers. Also referred to as Ezeiza Airport, it has over 30 air carriers with many direct flights from Atlanta, Georgia, Auckland, New Zealand, Barcelona, Spain, and Capetown, South Africa.

El Paso International Airport (airport code ELP) is located 6 miles east of downtown El Paso, Texas, in the western part of the state. Considered the gateway to West Texas and Southern New Mexico, the airport handles over 3 million passengers each year. El Paso has seven airlines providing non-stop service to eight major city hubs. The airport's two-level terminal is divided into East and West Concourses. With I-10 only 1.7 miles north, rental cars, taxis, shuttles and buses are available. Sun Metro runs a regular Airport Bus seven days a week. El Paso is home to NASA's Training Center for Shuttle Astronauts where they practice landing in simulated aircraft.

Kansas City International Airport (airport code MCI) is located 15 miles northwest of downtown Kansas City, Missouri. Opened in 1972, the airport has several transportation options available including Metro bus service (Monday through Friday), taxis, shuttles, rental cars and limousines. The airport has 15 airlines and non-stop service to 51 cities in the US, Canada and Mexico. More commonly referred to as KCI, the airport is in the Top 50 busiest US airports with just under 10 million passengers each year. The airport has three terminals, A, B and C. Adjacent to the airport is an 800-acre LEED®-certified business park called Intermodal BusinessCentre that will house national and international companies.

Sir Seewoosagur Ramgoolam International Airport (airport code MRU) is located on the island country of Mauritius near the east coast of Africa in the Indian Ocean. Also known as SSR Airport, Ramgoolam Airport is near Mahébourg about 48 kilometers southeast of the capital of Port Louis. Fifteen airlines provide service to Mauritius from Europe, the Middle East, Asia and Africa. The current terminal, Terminal 1, is a two-level structure with arrivals on the lower level and departures on the upper level. A new Terminal 2 is under construction and will connect with Terminal 1. Taxis, buses and rental cars provide transport to and from the airport and throughout the country.

Harrisburg International Airport (airport code: MDT) is conveniently located in South Central Pennsylvania near the state's capital and serves as an efficient gateway to/from the region. MDT is served by six airlines with 14 nonstop destinations and 100s of connections worldwide. The intuitive layout of the state-of-the-art terminal makes way finding around the terminal and three concourses less hassle and customer-friendly.  MDT prioritizes enhancing the airport experience for business and leisure travelers alike by offering a variety of passenger amenities: rocking chairs, free wifi, a variety of restaurants, shops and newsstands, a free frequent flyer lounge (for qualifying passengers), affordable onsite parking, internet kiosks and more.  Harrisburg International Airport also is home to a multi-modal transportation facility that is connected directly to the terminal and easily accessible by car, bus, taxi, shuttle and home to the rental car agencies serving MDT.  While MDT is the booking code for Harrisburg International Airport, it also stands for the Money, Distance and Time saved by choosing to fly to/from Harrisburg!

Louisville International Airport (airport code SDF) is located 10 minutes away from the city of Louisville, Kentucky. Kentucky's 2nd busiest airport, Louisville Airport hosts over 3 million passengers each year and has eight airlines providing non-stop service to 28 destinations around the country. The airport has two concourses, A and B. Located near the intersection of I-65 and I-264, rental cars, taxis, limousines, buses and hotel shuttles provide transport into the city and surrounding area. Louisville Airport is centrally located providing access to several major metropolitan areas, such as Lexington, Kentucky, Indianapolis, Indiana, and Nashville, Tennessee. With a UPS Worldport hub, Louisville Airport is the nation's 3rd busiest cargo airport.

Daytona Beach International Airport (airport code DAB) is located 3 miles southwest of Daytona Beach city center and adjacent to Daytona International Speedway. The gateway to Central Florida, Daytona Airport is close to the Atlantic Ocean, Orlando, Florida, Kennedy Space Center and St. Augustine, Florida. The airport has two terminals, Domestic Terminal, serving Delta Airlines, US Airways and Air Gate, and International Terminal with flights to the Bahamas. The airport unofficially began in 1906 when air travel was in its infancy and new pilots took to landing aircraft on the beach at Daytona because of the long, hard and smooth surface. What became airport's current location was built in 1930.

Amsterdam Airport Schiphol (airport code AMS) is located just 14 kilometers southwest of this capital city. Schiphol Airport has one terminal, which is divided into six piers (B through G) extending out from a central plaza. From Schiphol passengers can hop a 20-minute Direct Rail Link train to Amsterdam's Centraal Station and then connect to trains traveling throughout the Netherlands and into Germany and Belgium. From canals to coffee, Amsterdam is a relaxing city with few cars because the residents either walk or ride bikes. Strolling can be an outdoor activity along the tree-lined streets or indoor at one of the city's many famous art museums. Schiphol Airport is a destination unto itself because of its open-air promenade and observation deck on top of the terminal building and the mini-Rijksmuseum featuring a permanent collection of the 17th Century Dutch Masters located on Holland Boulevard, between Piers E and F.

Austin-Bergstrom International Airport (airport code AUS) serves the city of Austin and Central Texas. It has one terminal named for former Congresswomen Barbara Jordan and has three levels, Baggage Claim, Concourse and Mezzanine. Located eight miles from Austin, eleven airlines serve the airport providing 36 non-stop destinations in the US. The airport has a Family Viewing Area near the east runway with one acre set aside for viewing plane take offs and approaches. Austin is the state capital of Texas and home to the University of Texas. Showcasing the city's diverse music scene, the airport features live music each afternoon on one of several stages throughout the airport.

Newark Liberty International Airport (airport code EWR) opened in 1928 making it the nation's oldest airfield and it contains the country's first commercial airline terminal. Gateway to the 2nd largest metropolitan area in the world (only 14 miles from Manhattan), Newark Liberty serves a crucial role in the New York-New Jersey-Pennsylvania metropolitan area. AirTrain Newark connects passengers to the Newark Liberty train station where they can connect to NJ Transit or Amtrak railways for travel throughout New Jersey or to New York, Philadelphia and beyond. Part of the Port Authority of New York & New Jersey, Newark Liberty has three terminals, A, B, and C. Currently being renovated, Terminal B serves international arrivals. Newark Liberty hosts the world's longest commercial passenger flight, Newark to Singapore (Singapore Airlines), which runs 18 hours and 50 minutes, and the airport served over 33 million passengers in 2010.

Bob Hope Airport (airport code BUR) is located 3 miles northwest of downtown Burbank, California. Named for the Hollywood entertainer, Bob Hope Airport is the closest airport to downtown Los Angeles and the areas of Hollywood, Pasadena, Glendale, and Griffith Park. The airport consists of two terminals, Terminal A, renovated in 2002, and Terminal B. Downtown LA is reached via Southern California's only airport Metro station. Rental cars and buses are also available. Seven airlines transport over 4.5 million annual passengers to 13 non-stop US cities. With its proximity to Hollywood, the airport has been featured in several films include Giant (1956) and Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade (1989).

Doha International Airport (airport code DOH) in Qatar is on an international fast-track with over 15 million passengers in 2010. Qatar is currently building a new airport right next to the existing one, scheduled to open in 2012 with completion in 2015. The existing airport has two terminals, Terminals A (formerly called Departures) and B. Part of Terminal A is the Premium Terminal area, associated with Qatar Airways, providing Five Star hospitality for First and Business Class travelers. Located 4 kilometers from the city center, Doha provides transportation through Karwa Public Service, which provides bus service from the airport and throughout the city. Qatar sits on a peninsula in the Arabian Gulf neighboring Saudi Arabia and a day's drive from United Arab Emirates. Although it sits on giant reserves of natural gas and oil, Qatar continues to build its reputation as a world-class tourist destination with spas, resorts and beaches.
