desc.en: William P. Hobby Airport (airport code HOU) is located 7 miles south of downtown Houston, Texas, and is the city's oldest commercial airport. The airport consists of a Central Concourse with 26 gates. Hobby Airport handles domestic flights (international flights use George Bush Intercontinental) and is a regional center for corporate and private aircraft. Hobby consistently ranks in the Top 5 for customer service by J.D. Power and Associates for the last few years. Currently five air carriers and one charter service have operations at the airport, which hosts nearly 8.5 million passengers per year.  Ground transportation is provided by Houston Metro bus service, taxis, rental cars and SuperShuttle.

El Dorado International Airport (airport code BOG) is located in the capital of Bogotá, Colombia, in South America. The airport is the 3rd busiest in Latin America hosting almost 19 million passengers each year and is Latin America's busiest cargo airport. The airport has two passenger terminals. The main terminal called El Dorado has two concourses and handles international and domestic arrivals. The other terminal is called Puente Aereo (Air Bridge) and serves Colombia's Avianca Airlines and its subsidiaries exclusively. Located 13 kilometers from downtown, taxis and buses can take passengers into the city. Over 25 airlines provide travelers service to and from North and South America, the Caribbean and Europe.

Manchester Airport (airport code MAN) in England is located 24 kilometers south of the city and hosts almost 24 million passengers annually. Manchester Airport has over 65 airlines flying direct to almost 200 destinations. The airport has three terminals, 1, 2, and 3. Passengers can get to and from airport by taxi, bus, shuttle, or car rentals services. A Metrolink train linking the airport to the city center is scheduled for completion in 2016. The airport has three cycle bays for people using the bicycle routes to the airport. The Radisson SAS Airport Hotel offers a Shower and Change service in Terminal 2 for travelers needing to freshen-up between flights.

The Palma de Mallorca Airport (airport code PMI) was originally created to handle the island's postal service and now handles over 20 million people each year. Known in English as Majorca, Mallorca Airport has one terminal with four modules, labeled A, B, C, and D, branching from it. Although located 8 kilometers from the capital, everything on the island is easily connected by car, bus or taxi. Mallorca Airport is owned by Aena Aeropuertos as are 47 other Spanish airports. Conscious of the environment, Mallorca Airport has ISO certification as well as continued noise reduction and insulation practices with surrounding residential areas. Located in the Mediterranean Sea, the island of Mallorca is the largest of the Balearic Islands and has 550 kilometers of coastline. It receives 11 million visitors annually with Germany accounting for the largest number of travelers while Spain and the UK follow close behind.

(All commercial flights have been suspended because of civil war; they are expected to resume as early as December 1, 2011) Tripoli International Airport (airport code TIP) is located in 34 kilometers south of central Tripoli, Libya. The airport has two terminals, National and International, however, the National Terminal has been closed for new construction and all flights are being handled by the International Terminal. With an estimated 3 million passengers each year, the airport has 13 airlines serving Africa, the Middle East and Europe. Buses and taxis are readily available for transport into the city as well as throughout the country. Tripoli is situated in one of North Africa's best natural harbors and has historical ruins from the Roman and Ottoman empires. Tripoli is considered the gateway to the Sahara.

Chhatrapati Shivaji International Airport (airport code BOM), located 26 kilometers north of Mumbai, is one of India's busiest airports and the 2nd busiest South Asian airport with over 29 million passengers in 2010. Chhatrapati has three terminals, Terminal 1A, 1B and 1C serving domestic travelers, Terminal 2 for international travelers and a third terminal for cargo. Originally two airports, Sahar International and Santa Cruz Airport, they are now connected by a 15-minute ride on free shuttle buses for international travelers connecting to domestic flights. Terminal 1B and Terminal 2 have recently undergone extensive renovations to upgrade systems and prepare the airport for an expected growth of 40 million annual passengers.

Detroit Metropolitan Airport (airport code DTW) serves more than 32 million passengers a year. It has two terminals, the North Terminal and the McNamara Terminal. The airport is 20 miles (32 km) southwest of downtown Detroit. Although there is no rail service from the airport, there are plenty of rental cars, taxis, shuttles and buses available to points throughout the region including the University of Michigan in Ann Arbor, only 25 miles (43 km) away. The airport operates continuous, free shuttle service connecting the two terminals.  As a major hub for Delta Air Lines and the SkyTeam Alliance, DTW serves as the primary U.S. gateway for Delta flights to Asia. Together, 11 airlines provide more than 600 flights per day from DTW to destinations on four continents.  The 400-room, AAA four-diamond Westin Detroit Metro Airport hotel is connected directly to the airport at the McNamara Terminal and, as part of a pilot program with TSA, allow registered guests to pass through security to enjoy the terminal's more than 100 shops, restaurants and services.

Alicante International Airport (airport code ALC) is just 9 kilometers south of Alicante on the Mediterranean coast and is the gateway to the Costa Blanca resort region. It is the 6th busiest airport in Spain with just under 10 million passengers annually. In March 2011, the New Terminal Area (Terminal N) opened with the capability to handle 20 million passengers each year. Also included in the new construction is a parking facility, new access road and extended aircraft apron and taxiway. Transport to and from the airport is by rental cars, buses and taxis. Alicante Airport meets and exceeds the goals of the UNE-EN ISO 14001 standard for environmental management.

Greater Rochester International Airport (airport code ROC) is located just 3 miles southwest of downtown Rochester, in north central New York State on Lake Ontario.  The airport has two concourses, Frederick Douglass Concourse A, and Susan B. Anthony Concourse B. Sections of the terminal buildings are under renovation. Eight airlines serve the airport with 20 non-stop flights throughout the US as well as Toronto, Canada. The Fairfield Inn by Marriot Rochester Airport is located within walking distance from the main terminal. Rental cars, taxis, hotel shuttles, limousines and buses all provide transportation into Rochester. Eastman Kodak, Xerox Square and Bausch & Lomb Headquarters are all less than 20 minutes away.

McCarran International Airport (airport code LAS) in Las Vegas, Nevada, is the 6th busiest airport in the United States and the world's 19th busiest serving almost 40 million passenger annually. Named for a former Nevada Senator, the airport has two terminals, 1 and 2, with Terminal 2 serving international travelers. Terminal 3 is scheduled to open in 2012. Just a few minutes' drive from the southern end of the famous Las Vegas Strip, McCarran Airport provides easy transfers using shuttle vans, buses and rental cars. Limousines are available curbside for larger groups. With Las Vegas being the gambling capital of the US, there are 1,300 slot machines throughout the airport.

Denver International Airport (airport code DEN) serves the Denver metropolitan area and the Colorado Rocky Mountain Region. It is the 5th busiest airport the United States and 11th busiest in the world. Identifiable by its peaked fiberglass roof, Denver Airport opened in 1995 and in less than 20 years has become a major transportation hub handling over 50 million passengers annually. The airport has a two-sided main terminal and three concourses, A, B, and C. The passenger bridge between Jeppeson Terminal and Concourse A is 45.61 feet above the taxiway allowing passengers to watch planes taxi below. Located 23 miles northeast of downtown, taxis, buses and rental cars are available.

Zurich Airport (airport code ZRH) is located in Zurich, Switzerland, and is the 12th busiest airport in Europe with over 22 million passengers. Located approximately 11 kilometers north of the city center, the Swiss Federal Railways train takes only 15 minutes to the Zurich Hauptbahnfhof (main train station). Taxis, buses and rental cars are also available. The airport has one passenger terminal with Concourses A, B and E. An underground train takes passengers from the A and B concourses to the separate Concourse E. Centrally located, Zurich is home to many worldwide financial institutions and situated on the shores of Lake Zurich appealing to both business and leisure travelers.

LaGuardia Airport (airport code LGA) in New York City has been serving passengers since 1939. Operated by the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey, which also operates JFK and Newark airports, LaGuardia is located in the borough of Queens about 8 miles from midtown Manhattan. LaGuardia has four terminals, Central Terminal, US Airways Terminal, Delta Air Lines Terminal and Marine Air Terminal/Terminal A that serves international passengers. For travel to and from the city, taxis and rental cars work best and there is bus service to subway stations that connect to other locations around New York City and beyond. With more than 20 airlines flying to cities in the US, Canada and the Caribbean, LaGuardia has over 1,000 daily landings and takeoffs.  Less than 4 miles from LaGuardia are Citi Field, home to baseball's New York Mets, and the USTA National Tennis Center, home to the US Open.

Will Rogers World Airport (airport code OKC) is located about 6 miles from downtown Oklahoma City, Oklahoma. Named for Oklahoma native and legendary entertainer Will Rogers, the airport host over 3 million passengers each year. Rogers Airport has one terminal with two concourses, West and Central. The terminal recently underwent expansion and modernization of the arrival and baggage claim areas to better serve customers and business clients, such as the Oklahoma City Thunder NBA team and their opponents. Six major airlines provide the airport flights to 19 non-stop destinations across the US. Conveniently located near I-44 (Will Rogers Expressway), taxis, shuttles, buses and rental cars provide transport into Oklahoma City.

Albuquerque International Sunport (airport code ABQ) is New Mexico's largest commercial airport welcoming over six million people a year. The airport has three terminals, 1, 2 and 3, with Terminal 3 divided into Concourses A and B. A hub for Southwest Airlines, which handles over 50% of the airport's passengers, Southwest's Reservations Center is located adjacent to the airport. Sunport is currently undergoing renovations to create new concession locations, add restrooms, expand gate holding areas and incorporate environmentally friendly building systems. Sunport shares its runways with Kirtland Air Force Base, which provides rescue and firefighting aircraft services. At 5,352 feet in elevation, Sunport is over one mile above sea level.

Lisbon International Airport, Aeroporto de Lisboa, (airport code LIS) is located near Lisbon, Portugal, and serves over 14 million passengers annually. About 6.5 kilometers from the city center, taxis, buses and rental cars are available for transport, with plans underway to connect the Lisbon Metro to the airport by underground station. The airport has two terminals, Terminal 1, which handles arrivals and departures, while Terminal 2 is departures only. The airport has a full-service business center with meeting rooms and 90-seat amphitheater. The airport is one of the largest in size in Southern Europe with over 30 airlines and provides service not just to Europe, but Africa and South America.

Munich International Airport (airport code MUC) is located 27 kilometers northeast of Munich, the capital of Bavaria in Southern Germany. The airport features an Airport Center between two terminals, 1 and 2. Munich is the 2nd busiest airport in Germany and the 7th in Europe in passenger traffic hosting over 34.5 million passengers each year. Access the S-Bahn by underground rail station to get to Munich's Hauptbahnhof (main rail station). Voted 4th Best Airport in Europe by Skytrax, the airport's Visitor's Park features an 18-hole mini-golf course and playground and a Viewing Terrace on Level 07 of Terminal 2 for watching the airplanes take off and land on the eastern side.

Washington Dulles International Airport (airport code IAD) is located in Chantilly, VA, about 26 miles from Washington, D.C. The airport consists of a Main Terminal and several midfield concourses, A, B, C, and D. The airport is connected to D.C. by the Airport Access Highway, which runs directly to the Capital Beltway. To better serve passengers, the airport is currently planning a 23-mile extension of the Metrorail system with completion by 2016. The Metrorail will also pass through two major employment corridors, Tysons Corner and Reston-Herndon. Dulles Airport has 82 nonstop US destinations and 48 nonstop international destinations. As the nation's capital, Washington D.C. is home to the President, Congress and the Supreme Court and every nation that has diplomatic relationships with the US has an embassy in D.C. It is also home to 16 Smithsonian museums, the Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts and 70% of the city is national parkland.

Sydney International Airport (airport code SYD) is located 8 kilometers from the center of Sydney, Australia. With over 35.5 million passengers, Sydney Airport is Australia's busiest airport and the 28th busiest in the world. Sydney Airport is considered the gateway to Australia serving 46 international, 23 domestic and 28 regional destinations. T1 is the airport's international terminal, T2 is the domestic terminal and T3 serves Qantas Airlines exclusively as their domestic terminal. Airport Link connects both the international and domestic terminals by 10-minute train to the Central Railway Station in Sydney. Voted a Top 10 International Airport by readers of Condé Nast Magazine, Sydney airport is currently upgrading T1.

Magas is an airport in the Republic of Ingushetia near Ordzhonikidzevskaya,serving the capital city of Magas and largest region city of Nazran. The name Magas comes from the medieval capital of Alania. The name is translated from Ingush as a Sun City. Prior to 1992 Magas Airport was a Soviet military air base

Punta Cana International Airport (airport code PUJ) is located in the Caribbean country of the Dominican Republic and sees almost 4 million visitors a year. The airport is 3 miles from the Highüey-Punta Cana Highway and, depending on location, seaside resorts are a 10- to 40-minute drive from the airport via shuttle buses, taxis or rental cars. The airport has three terminals, all featuring palm frond thatched-roofs and live merengue music. Terminal 1 is for international flights while Terminal 3 is for domestic flights and private jets. Opened in 2009, Terminal 2 also serves international travelers on 53 different airlines. Punta Cana is the 2nd busiest airport in the Caribbean

Hartsfield-Jackson Atlanta International Airport (airport code ATL) is the world's busiest serving 90 million domestic and international passengers. The airport has spent the last decade making major improvements, including a fifth runway and an elevated SkyTrain, which led the Air Transport Research Society to name Atlanta the world's most efficient airport in 2011. Atlanta Airport is currently updating the Maynard H. Jackson Jr. International Terminal to be finished Spring 2012. Located 10 miles from downtown, passengers can get to and from the airport using the Metropolitan Transit Authority (MARTA) rail service station along with buses, shuttles, and rental cars. For passengers with pets, the airport has two pet areas. One is a 1,000 square-foot park at the Ground Transportation area Terminal South, doors W1 and W2. This fenced-in dog park has biodegradable bags, grass, rocks, and benches. A second pet area is located at the lower level of Terminal North.

Paris-Orly Airport or Aéroport d'Orly (airport code ORY) is the 11th busiest airport in Europe with over 25 million passengers each year. The airport has two terminals, Terminal Sud (South) with Halls A (Schengen/domestic) and B (non-Schengen/international) and Terminal Ouest (West). The free OrlyVAL shuttle provides transit between the terminals. Located about 14 kilometers south of Paris, France, travel into the city is available by shuttles, taxis, buses and rental cars. A tramway is expected to open in 2013 connecting the South Terminal to the Villejuif-Louis Aragon station. With over 40 air carriers, Paris-Orly Airport hosts travelers from North and South America, Africa and Asia.

Salt Lake City International Airport (airport code SLC) is located just west of Salt Lake City, Utah. Close to I-80, rental cars, taxis, shuttles and buses all provide transportation to the airport. The airport consists of three terminals. Terminal 1 has Concourses A and B, Terminal 2 has Concourse C, and the third terminal is the International Terminal with Concourses D and E. Nine US air carriers provide service to the airport with Delta Airlines operating out of Terminal 2 while all other airlines operate out of Terminal 1. Serving 21 million passengers each year, Salt Lake City Airport ranks as the 25th busiest North American airport with 90 non-stop destinations.

Edmonton International Airport (airport code YEG) is located 29 kilometers south of Edmonton, capital of Alberta province in Canada. The airport currently has one two-level terminal, however, the airport will be undergoing a major expansion starting in 2012. Linked by Highway 2, taxis, limousines and rental cars are available. Airporter bus has service into the city and Sundog Transportation provides shuttles throughout Alberta. The airport has 17 air carriers providing service across Canada, the US and Mexico and two flights to Europe - Frankfurt, Germany and London, UK. Canada's 5th busiest airport, it hosts over 6 million passengers each year. The Courtyard by Marriot Airport Hotel is scheduled to open Fall 2012.

Nashville International Airport (airport code BNA) is located eight miles east of downtown and serves Central Tennessee and the mid-southern states area. The airport features the Robert C. H. Mathews Jr. Terminal building with three levels. Level 1 is Ground Transportation, Level 2 is Baggage Claim and Level 3 is Ticketing and Concourse. The airport is served by twelve airlines linking Nashville to the US and Canada. Getting to and from the airport is easy with Super Shuttle International and Gray Line Airport Express providing service to downtown and other areas. Known as Music City USA, Nashville is home to the Country Music Hall of Fame and the Grand Ole Opry.

Tenerife Sur (South) Airport (airport code TFS) is one of two airports on Tenerife in the Canary Islands. The other is Tenerife North Airport (TFN). The North Airport handles mostly inter-island flights and Spanish air carriers while the larger South Airport hosts over 40 airlines from all over the world. Located on the resort side, Tenerife South sees over 7 million passengers annually. The South Airport is about 60 kilometers from Santa Cruz, the capital of Tenerife. Cars, buses and taxis are available to take people all over the island. Operated by Aena Aeropuertos, Tenerife South Airport is a leader in the European Management and Audit Scheme (EMAS) for sustainability.

Warsaw Chopin Airport (airport code WAW) in Poland hosts more than 8 million passengers each year. Named after the Polish pianist and composer Fryderyk Chopin, the airport integrated two terminals, formerly called Terminals 1 and 2, into the completely upgraded Terminal A building in 2010. Built in 2005, the General Aviation Terminal hosts private and corporate aircraft with state-of-art baggage handling and business services along with border and customs control for private and corporate aircraft. Located 10 kilometers from the city center, buses, taxis and rental cars are available. To promote its cultural namesake, Chopin Airport supports the National Fryderyk Chopin Institute and its "Chopin and his Europe" festival every year.

Stockholm Arlanda Airport (airport code ARN) is located about 45 kilometers north of Stockholm, the capital of Sweden. The airport has four terminals, Terminal 2 (Arlanda South) and Terminal 5 (Arlanda North) are international, Terminal 3 (Arlanda South) is for regional carriers and Terminal 4 (Arlanda South) is for domestic flights. The Arlanda Express train takes passengers on a high-speed rail line to Stockholm's Central Station. Buses and rental cars are also available. The airport hosts over 16.5 million annual travelers and has 84 airlines flying to 172 domestic and international destinations. The airport also has 50 conference rooms available for up to 700 people. Stockholm Airport has four hotels.

Manila Ninoy Aquino International Airport (airport code MNL) is the main gateway to the Manila Metro Area and all the Philippines islands. Manila Airport has four terminals, 1, 2, and 3, which oversee international travelers, and Domestic Terminal serving local carriers. The airport managed more than 27 million passengers in 2010, which put it in the top 50 for world's busiest airports. Served by 29 airlines, the airport is also a hub for travel throughout Asia. About four miles south of Manila, there is a 2-kilometer taxi ride to the Light Rail Transit line that takes travelers into the city. The Manila Airport Hotel is on-site next to Terminal 1.

Cleveland Hopkins International Airport (airport code CLE) is located 10 miles south of downtown Cleveland, Ohio. The Rapid Transit Authority (RTA) Red Line takes passengers from the airport to Tower City Center downtown. Located conveniently near both I-71 and I-90, limos, taxis and rental cars are also available. The 36th busiest airport in the US, Hopkins International hosts more than 11 million passengers each year. Nine air carriers provide service with Continental Airlines using Cleveland as a hub. Cleveland's central US location provides the airport with access to 43 percent of the US population. The airport consists of one passenger terminal divided into four concourses, A, B, C, and D.

Marrakech-Menara Airport (airport code RAK) is located 6 kilometers southwest of the center of Marrakech in central Morocco. The airport has two terminals, 1 and 2. Terminal 1 opened in 2008 and is partially powered by solar energy. As one of Africa's Top 20 busiest airports, Marrakech handles almost 3 million passengers per year. Transport into the city is by public bus, car rental or taxi. Originally a US Army Air Force Base during World War II, over 50 air carriers provide service to travelers from Arabia and Europe. Flights from North America transfer from Casablanca. In case of a medical emergency, Marrakech Airport has nurses on duty 24/7.

Soekarno-Hatta International Airport (airport code CKG) is located in Cengkareng, West Jakarta on the island of Java in the country of Indonesia. The airport is 20 kilometers from Jakarta city center. The airport has three terminals hosting over 44.5 million travelers each year. International arrivals are in Terminal 2 along with domestic flights from Garuda and Merpati Airlines while other domestic flights arrive and depart from Terminal 1 and the newly opened Terminal 3. Terminal 4 is under construction. Over 40 airlines serve the airport that is often called Cengkareng by locals. Taxis, shuttles and rentals are all available for transport. The Jakarta Airport Hotel is located inside Terminal 2E.

Los Angeles International Airport (airport code LAX) is the world's busiest origin and destination airport. Origin and destination passengers are those who begin or end their trips at LAX rather than connecting. LAX  is the 7th busiest airport in the world and has nine passenger terminals including the newly renovated Tom Bradley International Terminal. It is the only airport to have a US Coast Guard Air Station on-site. Gateway to Southern California, passengers can find all kinds of airport information from various sources such as listening to LAX Air Radio 530, picking up a copy of LAX Magazine, or watching videos on You Tube. In 2010 the Observation Deck at the LAX Theme Building (designed by Disney) reopened after being closed since 9/11. Fully renovated, the deck is open Saturdays and Sundays from 8 a.m. to 5 p.m. and is free to the public including free telescopes (parking fees apply).

Louis Armstrong New Orleans International Airport (airport code MSY) is located in Jefferson Parish, Louisiana, about 10 miles west of downtown New Orleans. New Orleans Airport services the city of New Orleans and the entire Gulf Coast region. Hosting between 7 and 8 million passengers each year, the airport consists of a passenger terminal divided into East and West with four concourses, A through D. Concourse C serves international passengers. Taxis, rental cars, airport shuttles and public buses all provide transportation into New Orleans. Named for famous jazz musician and New Orleans native Louis Armstrong, the airport has 10 airlines providing non-stop service to over 35 US cities and Canada.

San Juan Luis Muñoz Marín International Airport or Aeropuerto Internacional de Luis Muñoz Marín (airport code SJU) is located in Isla Verde, Puerto Rico, 3 miles southeast of the capital of San Juan. The airport is the 12th busiest in Latin America and one of the busiest in the Caribbean. The airport has a Main Terminal with four concourses and a new terminal with one concourse. Major hotels offer shuttle service to and from the airport. Otherwise taxis, rental cars and shared shuttles can transport travelers. Named for Puerto Rico's first democratically-elected governor, Marín Airport serves as a gateway to the Caribbean islands and sees 8.5 million passengers each year.

Portland International Jetport (airport code PWM) is the gateway to Maine and the rest of New England. With service from seven airlines, Portland provides direct links to the eastern US and Canada including direct flights to Atlanta, Chicago, and Philadelphia as well as Halifax, Nova Scotia, Quebec City, Canada, and London, England. Reopened in October 2011, the Jetport Terminal has been expanded to better serve the 1.8 million travelers the airport sees each year. Portland is a major cruise ship destination with over 90,000 ship passengers in 2011. Just a five minute drive from the Jetport is downtown Portland, voted one of Forbes Magazine "Most Livable Cities' in 2009.

Birmingham Airport (airport code BHX) is located 13 kilometers southeast of Birmingham, England, and is almost midway between London and Manchester. The airport is Top 50 for busiest European airports with over 9 million passengers annually. Travelers getting to the airport can do so by car using the M42 or can reach the train via the free Air-Rail Link shuttle. Local and long-distance buses are also available. The airport has two terminals, 1 and 2, connected by the Millennium Link walkway. The new three-story International Pier of Terminal 1 opened in 2009. The airport has over 20 airlines flying to five continents. Birmingham is also the closest airport to Shakespeare's birthplace, Stratford-upon-Avon.

Huntsville International Airport (airport code HSV) is located in northern Alabama. Called the Rocket City because of history with US space missions and other high-tech businesses, the airport is 12 miles from downtown Huntsville via I-565 and is easily accessed through shuttles, buses, taxis and rental cars. Huntsville Airport has six major carriers with non-stop service to cities such as Baltimore, Orlando, Chicago, Memphis, Houston and Denver. The Sheraton Four Points Hotel is located in the airport on the eastern side of the terminal and has 146 guest rooms and 10 meeting rooms. Also connected to the airport is the 18-hole par 72 Sunset Landing Golf Course open year around.

Malaga-Costa del Sol Airport (airport code AGP) is located in the resort area of Costa del Sol (Coast of the Sun) on the Mediterranean Sea and is the southernmost airport in Continental Europe. Located 8 kilometers southwest of Malaga, Spain, trains, buses, taxis and rental cars are available for transportation. Handling over 12 million passengers annually, the airport has three terminals, Terminal 1, Terminal 2 and the recently constructed Terminal 3. Considered the gateway to Andalucia, 85% of its passenger traffic is international with non-stop flights from all over Europe. Malaga is the 4th busiest airport in Spain and Spain's oldest airport (built 1919) still in its original location.

Aeroport International Pierre-Elliot-Trudeau de Montreal (airport code YUL) or Montreal-Trudeau Airport serves the citizens of Montreal, Canada's 2nd largest city, and Eastern Canada. With 12 million passengers each year, Montreal-Trudeau has 32 air carriers with more than 130 direct flights to destinations in Canada and the US and is Canada's gateway to Europe. The airport has one terminal with three branches, one serving Canadians – Zone Domestique – a newly renovated section for US travelers – Zone Transfrontaliere USA - and one for International travelers – Zone Internationale. Located 20 kilometers from downtown Montreal, L'Aerobus shuttle runs between the airport and downtown every 30 minutes with a stop at Berri Terminal, Montreal's main bus terminal.

Beijing Capital International Airport (airport code PEK) in China is the busiest airport in Asia and the 2nd busiest in the world. The airport hosts over 73 million passengers annually with over 70 airlines flying to over 200 cities worldwide. The airport has three terminals. Terminal 1 handles domestic flights, while Terminal 2 handles international flights and flights between Hong Kong, Macau and Taiwan. Terminal 3 was constructed to handle visitors for the 2008 Olympics and is the 2nd largest terminal in the world. Located 20 kilometers north of central Beijing, the Airport Express Line runs from the airport directly into the city. Taxis and airport buses are also available.

London Gatwick Airport (airport code LGW) is the UK's 2nd largest airport, after Heathrow, and the busiest single-runway airport in the world. Hosting 33 million passengers annually, the airport serves more than 200 destinations in over 90 countries. Gatwick has two terminals, North and South. The airport is 28 miles south with easy access to central London by the Gatwick Express. Express tickets can be purchased in both terminals. Gatwick is bicycle accessible through the UK's National Cycle Network. Cyclists can bike a direct path to the South Terminal with parking. Gatwick recently began developing its future master plan to serve an expected 40 million passengers each year by 2020.

Charles de Gaulle Airport in Paris (airport code CDG) is Europe's 2nd busiest airport after London's Heathrow. It is located 23 kilometers northeast of Paris and connected by a 45-minute train ride to the city. Named for the President of the French Republic during WWII, Charles de Gaulle Airport has three terminals - Terminal 1 serves international travelers, Terminal 2 servers Air France and other European airlines while Terminal 3 serves charter flights only. Wooing international travelers for decades, Paris is home to such world-renowned marvels as the Louvre Museum, Notre-Dame Cathedral and the Eiffel Tower. Occupying a compact 2,723 square kilometers, the capital of France is home to over 11 million people. While the French refer to it as Aeroport Roissy, de Gaulle Airport has connections to TGV trains in Terminal 2 and can take visitors to Disneyland Paris in less than 12 minutes or to locations throughout France and on into Europe.

Bradley International Airport (airport code BDL) is located in Windsor Locks, Connecticut, just a 15-minute drive to Hartford. Considered the Gateway to New England, the airport is a 2-hour drive to Boston, Massachusetts and 1.5 hours from White Plains, New York.  The airport's Terminal A, has two concourses. The East Concourse has Gates 1-12 and the West Concourse Gates 20-30. Thirteen airlines serve the airport with flights from around the US and Canada. The Sheraton Hotel is located between Terminal A and the old Terminal B, which is scheduled for demolition. Connecticut Transit buses transport travelers between downtown Harford and Bradley Airport. Taxi, limos and rental cars are also available.

Imam Khomaini International Airport (airport code IKA) is located 30 kilometers southwest of central Tehran, Iran, and is accessible by car, taxi and bus via the Tehran-Qom Freeway. Twenty-three air carriers provide service to over 12 million passengers each year with destinations throughout the country and in Europe and Asia. The airport has one terminal between two concourses. There is also a CIP lounge for premium passengers. For travel within the country, a shuttle bus links Tehran Airport with Mehrabad Airport, which handles domestic flights. Construction is underway for an extension of the Tehran Metro to reach the airport as well as construction of a new airport hotel.

Calgary International Airport (airport code YYC) is located in Calgary, Canada, at the foot of the Canadian Rocky Mountains. The airport has one terminal divided into four concourses, A, B, C and D. Located 10.6 miles from downtown Calgary, the airport has a variety of transportation options including public buses along with taxis, airport shuttles, private vehicles and car rentals. Canada's 4th busiest airport, Calgary Airport sees over 12.5 million passengers each year. Served by over 20 airlines, Calgary Airport has 67 domestic and international non-stop destinations including Cancun, Mexico, Newark, New Jersey, Paris, France, and Tokyo, Japan. The Delta Airport Hotel is connected to the airport by indoor walkway.

Leonardo da Vinci International Airport, also known as Fiumicino to locals, (airport code FCO) is located 30 kilometers from the center of Rome. Fiumicino has four terminals, 1, 2, 3, and the recently opened Terminal 5 handling international travelers. Passengers wanting to visit the city center can use the Leonardo Express rail by going to the train station at the airport. The train runs every half hour and takes 30 minutes to Stazione Termini, Rome's main train station. Much like the city, the airport also has exceptional shopping from famous high-end fashion (Armani, Salvatore Ferragamo, Gucci) to duty free Italian-made products and traveler basics such as newsstands and gift shops. Also called the Eternal City, Rome's history runs 3,000 years deep and is home to 913 churches and countless historical ruins. These include must-see sites such as the Trevi Fountain, St. Peter's Basilica at the Vatican and the Coliseum.

Dallas Love Field (airport code DAL) is located 6 miles northwest of downtown Dallas, Texas. A city-owned, public use airport, Love Field currently has one terminal building serving Southwest Airlines, Continental Express, Delta, and American Airlines/American Eagle. Hosting over 7 million passengers a year, the terminal is undergoing a modernization project expected to be complete by 2014. The remodel includes a new concourse with 20 gates and an expanded baggage claim area. Rental cars, airport shuttles, taxis and Dallas Area Rapid Transit (DART) buses all provide transportation to and from the airport. The airport also features the Love Field Conference Center with state-of-the-art business amenities, catering and meeting rooms.

Des Moines International Airport (airport code DSM) is located three miles from the Des Moines business district and serves all of Central Iowa. An insurance and financial center, Des Moines has won awards including No. 1 by Forbes as "Best Place for Business and Careers' and No. 1 for "Best City to Live and Work' by Kiplinger's Finance. The airport handles approximately two million passengers per year and is in the top 100 most active commercial airports in the United States. Due to its central US location, Des Moines Airport also has a strong air cargo presence. There two concourses, A and C, that branch off the main terminal building.

King Abdulaziz International Airport (airport code JED) serves the city of Jeddah in Saudi Arabia. Started in 2006, the New KAIA Project is expected to have state-of-the-art facilities along with high-speed rail service constructed over the next 20 years. The new and expanded terminal is expected to open in 2014. The existing airport is still open and continues to host over 17 million passengers each year. There are currently two passenger terminals, North, which handles all foreign air carriers, and South, which handles Saudi Arabian, Mas Air and Sama Airlines. The KAIA also has a specially designed Hajj Terminal for pilgrims traveling to Mecca/Makkah as part of the annual Hajj.

Memphis International Airport (airport code MEM) is located 9 miles from the business center of East Memphis and 11 miles south of downtown Memphis, Tennessee. Memphis is home to worldwide shipping company Federal Express (FedEx), which uses Memphis Airport as a "SuperHub" making it the busiest and largest cargo airport in the world. Taxis and rental cars are available for transport between the airport and the city. The airport has three terminals, A, B and C.  Terminal B serves international flights. Eight airlines operate at the airport with non-stop service throughout the US as well as Toronto, Canada, and Amsterdam, Netherlands. The airport serves more than 10 million travelers annually.

Guarulhos International Airport (airport code GRU) is officially called Governador Andre Franco Montoro International Airport and is Sao Paulo, Brazil’s busiest airport handling over 20 million passengers annually. Located 30 kilometers northeast of the city, the Tropic of Capricorn intersects the airport’s southern tip. Locals refer to it as Cumbica Airport after the suburb it occupies. Guarulhos Airport has two terminals, Terminal 1 with Wings A and B and Terminal 2 with Wings D and C. However, the airport is undergoing a major expansion with construction of a third runway and a new Terminal 3 along with a new express rail service in preparation for the 2014 FIFA World Cup.

Diagoras International Airport (airport code RHO) is located on the Greek Isle of Rhodes near the city of Paradissi. The airport is 13 kilometers southwest of the city of Rhodes and is linked by bus service, taxis and car rentals. The airport's new terminal was completed in 2005. The 4th busiest airport in Greece, Diagoras Airport is served by over 50 air carriers, although most have only seasonal service. Aegean Airlines and Olympic Air have year-round service to several locations throughout Greece along with service to other cities in Europe. Located in the southeast Mediterranean Sea, Rhodes is a major sea port with links to Athens, Crete, Cyprus and Turkey.

Phoenix Sky Harbor International Airport (airport code PHX) is the nation's 10th busiest airport and is 18th busiest in the world for passenger traffic. Sky Harbor has three terminals, 2-4. Terminal 1 was demolished in 1990 after Terminal 4 was built and the other terminals were never renumbered. Each terminal has its own Pet Park for those traveling with companion animals. Located three miles east of downtown Phoenix, SuperShuttle offers 24-hour door-to-door service between the airport and resorts, hotels and homes throughout the Valley. Taxis and rental cars are also available. Seventeen airlines serve the airport. Sky Harbor recently received its sixth perfect FFA certification safety inspection in a row.

Queen Alia International Airport (airport code AMM) is located 35 kilometers from downtown Amman, Jordan, the nation's capital. Open in 1983, the airport hosts 5.5 million passengers each year. The airport has two passenger terminals, which are currently being upgraded, and is building a third terminal to open in 2012. Designated Airport Taxis provide transport along with buses and rental cars. A new rail line linking the airport to central Amman is under also construction. Over 35 airlines provide flights to Europe, the Middle East and Southeast Asia. It is also a hub for Royal Jordanian airlines which has flights to Chicago, Detroit, Montreal and New York in North America.

Jacksonville International Airport (airport code JAX) is located in Jacksonville, Florida, and services northeastern Florida and southeastern Georgia. Hosting almost six million passengers annually, the airport is 12 miles from downtown with taxi, shuttle and rental cars available. The airport has one two-level terminal and two concourses, A and C, and is served by eight air carriers with 27 non-stop US destinations. Both a business and vacation center, Jacksonville has 21 miles of beaches and convention space for up to 10,000 people. Jacksonville is also home to the NFL Jaguars and also hosts the annual Florida-Georgia college football game along with the Konica Minolta Gator Bowl on New Year's Day.

Taiwan Taoyuan International Airport (airport code TPE) is located Dayuan, Taiwan, 50 kilometers from the capital of Taipei. The airport is in the Top 30 busiest airports in Asia and hosts over 25 million passengers each year. The airport has two terminals. Terminal 1, with Concourses A and B, just recently finished a complete renovation. Terminal 2, opened in 2000, has two concourses, C and D (also called North and South). The Skytrain connects the terminals. Metropolitan Bus routes connect the airport with the Taipei train station and taxis and car rentals are also available. Over 35 airlines serve the airport with flights throughout Asia and Europe and North America.

Chennai International Airport (airport code MAA) is located in Tirusulam, India, about 12 kilometers southwest of Chennai, India's 4th largest city. It is the 3rd busiest airport in India handling some 10.5 million passengers. Chennai has two passenger terminals, Kamaraj Terminal for domestic travelers and Anna Terminal for international travelers. A third terminal handles cargo. A new domestic terminal is being built next to the existing one while Anna Terminal is undergoing expansion. Sometimes still referred by its former name, Madras Airport, Chennai is served by five domestic and 26 international air carriers. Suburban Rail Service provides transport into the city and is connected by underground passage to the airport.

Faro International Airport (airport code FAO) is located in Faro, Portugal, and handles more than 6 million passengers each year. The airport is 2.6 kilometers from the center of Faro on the southernmost coast of Portugal. Taxis, buses, rental cars and hotel shuttles offer efficient transport to and from the airport. The airport's Main Terminal was enlarged in 2001 and is currently undergoing other improvements to handle increased passenger capacity. A hub for Ryanair, over 40 air carriers provide service to travelers from destinations all over Europe. Gateway to the Algarve region of southern Portugal, Faro is nearby several beach resorts and the airport is busiest from March to October.

Barcelona-El Prat Airport (airport code BCN) is located southwest of Barcelona and is just 3 kilometers from the Port of Barcelona, a major Mediterranean container port. It serves the metropolitan area of Barcelona and El Prat. Although there has been a runway in place since 1916, Barcelona Airport didn't take off until the 1992 Olympics. The airport underwent major renovations to handle the 10 million travelers who attended. This refurbishment continues to today with the 2009 remodel of Terminal T1 while Terminal T2 is undergoing remodeling today to serve the 30 million passengers the airports now receives. There is also a new Corporate Aviation Terminal for business travelers and includes VIP lounges, meeting rooms and business center. To get into Barcelona proper from the airport, passengers can use the Aerobus, which departs from all three terminals. Travelers can also use the rail service or hire a taxi or rental car.

Minneapolis Saint Paul International Airport (airport code MSP) is in the middle of the twin cities and is also a short driving distance from the Minnesota metropolitan areas of Bloomington, Eagan, Brooklyn Park and Richfield. The airport ranks 15th in North America for passenger traffic and is the 12th busiest in the US with over 32 million travelers annually. The airport has two terminal buildings, Terminal 1-Lindberg and Terminal 2-Humphrey. A light rail system connects the airport to downtown Minneapolis, the Mall of America and several other locations. Buses, taxis, shuttles and rental cars are also available. Twelve air carriers provide non-stop service to 114 domestic and 21 international markets.

Pittsburgh International Airport (airport code PIT) is located 16 miles west of downtown Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania. The airport accommodates over 8 million passengers annually with over 155 non-stop flights per day to 37 destinations including non-stop flights to Europe. The airport terminal consists of two buildings, Landside Terminal and Airside Terminal. Concourses A, B, C and D branch off the Airside Terminal and are centered by the Airmall with shops and restaurants. The Hyatt Regency Hotel is attached to the Landside Terminal. By car, the airport is accessible by I-376, Exit 53. There is also public transportation to downtown through the Port Authority's new West Busway, along with taxis and shuttles.

Athens International Airport Eleftherios Venizelos (airport code ATH) is the 27th busiest airport in Europe located 27 kilometers northeast of the capital of Athens, Greece. Expanded and updated for the 2004 Olympics, the airport consists of a main terminal divided into areas A and B. There is also a satellite terminal for charter flights. Line 3 of the Metro takes about 35 minutes to the center of Athens. The Metro can also take travelers to the ferry terminals of Piraeus. Taxis, buses and rental cars are also available. With over 65 airlines handling over 15 million travelers, Athens Airport is a major connection between Asia, the Middle East and Europe.

Vienna International Airport (airport code VIE) in Vienna, Austria, is centrally located serving as a bridge between Eastern and Western Europe. Located19 kilometers southeast of the city center, it has regular bus service between the airport and Wien Mitte/ Landstrasse rail station. The airport has three terminals, Terminal 1, 2 and Terminal 1A serving low-cost air carriers. Concourses B, C, and D branch off of these terminals. The airport also has a VIP Terminal. The airport is undergoing expansion of the terminal areas, called Skylink, to serve even more passengers. Expected to be complete in 2012, Skylink will help Vienna Airport to handle more than 20 million passengers annually.

Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport (airport code DFW) is 4th busiest airport in the US and 8th busiest in the world. The airport has five terminals, A, B, C, D (serving international passengers), and E, which is currently undergoing construction to add 54,000 more square feet of interior space by 2017.  Terminals A and C serve American Airlines passengers exclusively. Dallas/Fort Worth Airport has two hotels attached to the airport, the Grand Hyatt DFW inside Terminal D and the Hyatt Regency DFW adjacent to Terminal C. The airport is 18 miles from downtown Dallas and 24 miles from downtown Fort Worth with a variety of transportation options from buses (through Dallas Area Rapid Transit – DART), rail lines (through Trinity Railway Express - TRE), taxis and rental cars. The Dallas/Fort Worth area is the 4th largest metropolitan region in the US featuring world-class attractions from amusements parks to art museums.

Tunis-Carthage Airport (airport code TUN) is located four miles from the capital city of Tunis, Tunisia. Africa's 10th busiest airport, Tunis is the country's largest city. Also named for the historical center of Carthage that sits just north of the airport, Tunis Airport hosts more than 4 million passengers annually. The airport consists of one Main Terminal with over 30 airlines providing service to destinations in Africa, Europe and the Middle East. Buses and taxis provide transport to and from the airport. A city with thousands of years of history, Tunis Airport is a natural gateway to the historically rich country of Tunisia and the beach resorts along its coast.

O.R. Tambo International Airport (airport code JNB) is the main air transportation hub for the city of Johannesburg and serves all of Southern Africa. Formerly called Johannesburg International Airport, the name was changed to O.R. Tambo, a South African liberation leader, in 2006. It hosts more than 17 million passengers annually. Recently updated for the 2010 FIFA World Cup, the airport has two terminals, A and B. Along with terminal improvements, the airport is currently upgrading its parking facilities and recently completed a Gautrain link from Sandton Station to the airport. With over 40 regional, national and international airlines from five continents, Tambo Airport connect Southern Africa with the world.

San Francisco International Airport (airport code SFO) is the world's 23rd busiest airport with over 39 million passengers annually. Considered the "Gateway to the Pacific,' San Francisco International Airport has over 50 air carriers and 31 non-stop destinations. The airport consists of a Main Hall with two branches, International A and International G for international travelers, and Terminals 1, 2, and 3 (Concourses B-F) handling domestic flyers. This airport was also the first major US airport to achieve 100% fully automated and integrated baggage screening. Located 14 miles south of downtown San Francisco, the Bay Area Rapid Transit (BART) systems can take travelers anywhere in the city easily and efficiently.

King Khalid International Airport (airport code RUH) is located 35 kilometers north of Riyadh, the capital of Saudi Arabia. The airport has three main passenger terminals. Terminal 1 is for international flights, Terminal 2 is also international, but serves Air France, Saudi Arabian Airlines and NAS Air only, while Terminal 3 is for domestic flights. There is also a Royal Terminal for high-ranking officials and heads of state. Hosting almost 13 million passengers each year, the airport's Mosque can accommodate 5,000 people inside and another 5,000 in the outside plaza. Eight car rental companies operate at the airport and the Sahara Airport Hotel is located near the commercial lounge complex.

George Bush Intercontinental Airport (airport code IAH) is the 8th busiest airport in the United States and is 3rd in the US for non-stop domestic and international service. It is also the nation's busiest airport providing service to Mexico with 30 destinations. Bush Intercontinental has five terminals, A, B, C, D, and E. Terminal E is the airport's newly opened international passenger terminal. A hub for Continental Airlines, the airport is 22 miles north of downtown Houston. To get to the city center, visitors can employ taxis, shuttles, rental cars or the city's bus service, the Metro. The underground inter-terminal train links passengers to all terminals and the Marriott Hotel located on-site. Houston has one of the world's longest passenger flights, a 17-hour flight from Houston to Dubai on Emirate Airlines.

T. F. Green Airport or Theodore Francis Green State Airport (airport code PVD) is located in Warwick, Rhode Island, 6 miles south of the capital of Providence. The airport hosts about 2.2 million passengers each year and is a reliever airport to Logan International in Boston, Massachusetts. Seven airlines provide non-stop service to 24 cities throughout the US and Toronto, Canada. The airport has one concourse, divided into North and South, and is named for former governor Bruce Sundlun. Rental cars, taxis, and buses can take passengers into Providence and surrounding areas. Currently the airport's runways are being refurbished and expanded and soon the airport concourses will also be expanded.

Kahului Airport (airport code OGG) is located on the Hawaiian island of Maui, also called the Valley Isle. Receiving both overseas and inter-island travelers, Kahului is the 2nd busiest airport in the state. Located on the narrow land bridge between the Haleakala volcano and the West Maui Mountain Range three miles east of Kahului town, cars, resort shuttles, taxis and public transit are all available. Kahului has two terminals, a main terminal and a commuter terminal. Thirteen local and national airlines have flights into Maui with over 5 million passengers each year. The airport-to-airport route of Honolulu-Kahului is one of the busiest in the US with 118,760 seats available daily.

The dual airports of Rio de Janeiro/Galeao Airport serving domestic travelers and Antonio Carlos Jobim International Airport (airport code GIG) together are located 20 kilometers from the center of Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, and make up the 7th busiest airport in Latin America. More commonly referred to as Galeao Airport, the airport is accessed by several expressways, such as the Red Line, Yellow Line and Brazil Avenue. Taxis, buses and rental cars are also available. Galeao Airport is connected to over 26 domestic locations and 24 international locations hosting over 12 million visitors each year. Over 20 airlines provide service to the airports two terminals, Terminals 1 and 2.

Midway International Airport (airport code MDW) in Chicago, Illinois, is Chicago's original airport, formerly called Chicago Municipal Airport, built in 1923. Midway has one Main Terminal and three concourses, A, B, and C, that are connected by the Midway Boulevard full of restaurants and retail shops. A variety of low-cost carriers serve the airport such as Southwest Airlines, Frontier Airlines and AirTran Airways. Only 8 miles from the downtown Loop, passengers can get to downtown Chicago by car on the Stevenson Expressway or by rail on the Chicago Transit Authority's Orange Line. One of top 30 busiest airports in the United States, Midway sees over 17 million passengers each year.

Auckland Airport (airport code AKL) is located 21 kilometers south of Auckland, New Zealand. Considered the gateway to New Zealand, over 70 percent of the country's visitors either enter or leave through Auckland Airport. Over 20 airlines serve more than 13 million travelers each year. The airport has two terminals, International and Domestic. A 15-minute walk separates the terminals. Located near a major motorway, the airport is easily accessed by taxi or rental car. Helicopter transfers are also available. Airbus operates bus service between the airport and the city every 20 minutes and takes only 30 to 35 minutes. Novetel Auckland Airport Hotel is located adjacent to the International Terminal.

Winnipeg James Armstrong Richardson International Airport (airport code YWG) is the 8th busiest airport in Canada with over 3 million passengers per year. Located 20 minutes northwest of downtown Winnipeg, the airport's unique central Canadian location serves the entire province of Manitoba as well as parts of Saskatchewan and North Dakota and northern Minnesota in the US. Named for a prominent Winnipeg businessman, the airport features a newly built four-level terminal that hosts 19 air carriers. The airport's website features a special Sun Destinations section offering travelers seasonal service to warm weather climates in the US, Mexico and the Caribbean. Airport transfers are provided by taxis, buses and rental cars.

Narita International Airport (airport code NRT) is located 57.5 kilometers east of Tokyo Station in the town of Narita and serves the greater Tokyo area of Japan. With over 35 million passengers annually, Narita Airport is the 2nd busiest airport in Japan and handles the majority of international travelers. The airport has two terminals, 1 and 2. Terminal 1 is divided into a North and South wing and handles 40 airlines. Terminal 2 consists of a Main Building and a Satellite Building and handles 25 airlines. Taxis and buses can transport passengers into Tokyo, but the quickest way is the JR Narita Express train only 1 hour to Tokyo Station.

Helsinki-Vantaa Airport (airport code HEL) is located about 19 kilometers north of the capital of Finland. The airport hosts over 12.8 million passengers each year and is the 4th busiest Nordic airport. The airport is divided into two terminals and linked by an internal pedestrian connection.  Only a 30-minute bus ride into the city, taxis and rental cars are also available. The cities of Tampere and Turku are only 170 kilometers away and St. Petersburg, Russia, at just under 300 kilometers away, is reachable via the E18 highway. Over 50 airlines have flights from North American, Europe and Asia.

Boston Logan International Airport (airport code BOS) is New England's largest transportation center located 3 miles across the harbor from downtown Boston. Logan Airport has four terminals, Terminal A, B, C, and E with walk times between Terminals A-C less than 10 minutes. Terminal E services international travelers and provides shuttle buses connecting to the other terminals. Terminals A and C feature Kidport, children's play areas where families can unwind and kids can play while waiting. Rocking chairs are also provided for families with infants. For travel into Boston the Massachusetts Port Authority (MassPort, which also operates the airport) provides public transportation by subway (10 minutes), bus (20 minutes), or water taxi (7 minutes) with free shuttle service to the ferry dock from the airport. Logan offers nonstop service to over 72 domestic locations and 30 international destinations. The Hilton Boston Logan Airport Hotel connects directly to Logan via skybridge.

Albany International Airport (airport code ALB) is the major airport serving Northeastern New York and Western New England. With seven airlines serving the US and Canada, Albany has non-stop service to 24 cities including Toronto, Boston, New York, Chicago, Las Vegas and Washington DC. The airport has one terminal with Level 1 ticketing and baggage claim, Level 2 gates and concessions and Level 3 administrative offices and a Public Observation Deck. The airport is six miles from the city center and has buses, rental cars and hotel shuttles available for transport. In 2000, Albany completed a multi-million dollar redevelopment expanding the terminal to 230,000 square feet to serve 1.2 million passengers.

Kos International Hippocrates Airport (airport code KGS) is located on the Greek island of Kos and is about 27 kilometers from the center of Kos town. Kos is a small island so buses, taxis and cars can provide easy transport not only from the airport, but all around the island. The airport has one Main Terminal. Over 30 airlines cater to more than 1.5 million passengers each year, usually with seasonal service to this mostly tourist destination. An hour flight from Athens, Aegean Airlines and Olympic Airlines handle the majority of domestic flights. Kos is the birthplace of Hippocrates, the "Father of Western Medicine," for whom the airport is named.

Melbourne Airport (airport code MEL) is located 22 kilometers northwest of Melbourne, the capital of Victoria, Australia. Also referred to as Tullamarine Airport for the suburb it resides in, Melbourne Airport is the 2nd busiest in Australia with over 26 million passengers each year. The airport has four terminals. T1 is the domestic terminal for Qantas and Jetstar. T2 is for international travelers. T3 is also domestic serving Virgin Blue and Rex and T4 is domestic for Tiger Airways. SkyBus offers express bus service between the airport and city center. Taxis and rental cars are also available. T2 is in the midst of an expansion plan to improve passenger experience.

Princess Juliana International Airport (airport code SXM) is located in the Caribbean on the shared island of Dutch Sint Maarten and French St. Martin. The airport is located 15 kilometers northwest of Sint Maarten's capital Philipsburg and 3.2 kilometers from St. Martin's capital Marigot. The 2nd busiest airport in the Caribbean, the airport is named for the crown princess of the Netherlands who landed here in 1944. The airport has recently built a new 4-story terminal building and has over 20 airlines with flights from North American and Europe. As the gateway to the Lesser Antilles the airport ferries travelers to the nearby islands of Anguilla, Saba and St. Barts.

Southwest Florida International Airport (airport code RSW) is located in Fort Myers, Florida, and serves the entire Southwest Florida Region, which includes the cities of Fort Myers, Naples, Sanibel Island, Marco Island, Bonita Springs and on into the Everglades. One of the busiest single-runway airports in the US, Southwest Florida Airport serves more than 7.5 million passengers each year on 16 airlines with non-stop service throughout North America and international service to Canada and Germany. The airport consists of a Main Terminal, opened in 2005, with Concourses B, C and D. LeeTran buses, taxis and rental cars are available for transportation from the airport and into the Southwest Florida Region.

Bahrain International Airport (airport code BAH) is located in the Kingdom of Bahrain, about 7 kilometers northeast of the capital city of Manama. The airport sees about 8.9 million passengers each year and is currently undergoing expansion to handle triple the capacity in the future. The existing terminal, Terminal 1, will be replaced with two new terminals. Taxis and rental cars are available for transport to and from the airport and around the country. Forty-three airlines currently serve the airport. Bahrain is a group of 33 islands situated in the Arabian Gulf off the coast of Saudi Arabia It is connected to mainland Saudi Arabia by the King Fahd Causeway.

Philadelphia International Airport (airport code PHL) serves the 5th largest metropolitan area in the United States and is owned and operated by the City of Philadelphia. Located seven miles southwest from downtown Philly, the airport is easily accessible by car from Interstates 76, 95 and 476 and also by rail service by the Southeastern Pennsylvania Transportation Authority's (SEPTA) High Speed Airport Line from all terminals. The airport has seven terminals, A-East and the recently built Terminal A-West (serving international travelers), B, C, D, E and F. Terminal F is already undergoing an expansion scheduled for completion in 2014. A high-end shopping corridor connects Terminals B and C. The Airport Marriott Hotel at PHL is the airport's only on-site hotel and is connected to Terminal B via skybridge. A city steeped in history, Philadelphia is considered the birthplace of the nation with plenty of historic sites within walking distance of each other.

Melbourne International Airport (airport code MLB) is located 1.5 miles northwest of downtown Melbourne, Florida, which is situated on eastern Florida's Space Coast. The Space Coast includes more than 70 miles of beaches, while Port Canaveral (the country's largest cruise ship port) is 25 miles away and the Kennedy Space Center is 48 miles away. The passenger terminal can accommodate up to 2 million annual travelers. Delta and US Airways provide non-stop service to their hubs in Atlanta and Charlotte, with connections around the world. Charter airlines Baer Air provides flights to the Bahamas and the US. The Florida Institute of Technology's Aviation Flight School is adjacent to the airport.

Frankfurt Airport (airport code FRA) sees over 52 million international passengers annually and is the world's 9th busiest international airport. Located in Germany, this central European airport is only a 3-hour flight from most major European cities and is nine hours from Chicago and 11 from Mumbai. The airport has two terminals, 1 and 2, with a third terminal under construction. Located 8 miles southwest of the city, there are two railway stations that can be accessed from the airport. The S-Bahn on Level 1 in Terminal 1 takes passengers into the city and the Deutsche Bahn Travel Center at the AIRail Terminal in Terminal 1, B Concourse, can take passengers throughout the region. For its many business passengers, the Frankfurt Airport also has a 36-room conference center that can serve up to 180 people and four on-site hotels including the Sheraton Frankfurt Airport Hotel and the Steigenberger Airport Hotel.

Vancouver International Airport (airport code YVR) is Canada's 2nd busiest airport. It was built in 1930 after famous aviator Charles Lindbergh's chided that Vancouver had "no fit field to land on.' Since then Vancouver has built an airport that provides a strategic location for routes between Asia and North America and, after a successful 2010 Winter Olympics, a popular tourist destination. Vancouver has two terminals, the Domestic Terminal and the International and USA Terminal. Approximately 12 kilometers from downtown Vancouver, passengers can get to and from the airport in 26 minutes using the Canada Line rapid transit rail link. Taxis, buses, and rental cars are also available. Vancouver is a major cruise ship port with some 177 ships each year. To get to the cruise ship port, look for cruise representatives in the Domestic Terminal, Level 2, and at the Canada Customs Hall or International Reception Lobby for international passengers.

Cincinnati/Northern Kentucky International Airport (airport code CVG) is located in Hebron, Kentucky, just 13 miles from downtown Cincinnati, Ohio. Opened back in 1947, the airport has three terminals, 1, 2, and 3 with three concourses, A, B and C. Concourse B serves international passengers. The airport serves the tri-state area of Kentucky, Ohio and Indiana and provides non-stop service to over 65 cities including Paris, France, Toronto, Canada, and Cancun, Mexico. Handling almost 5 million travelers in 2011, Cincinnati Airport is one of the fastest growing airports in the world. Several miles of horse riding trails surround the airport and are accessed by joining the CVG Equestrian Program.

Ibiza Airport (airport code IBZ) is located on the Spanish island of Ibiza, 3rd largest of the Balearic Islands in the Mediterranean Sea. The airport is 7.5 kilometers from Ibiza's capital, Cuidad de Ibiza. The Ibiza Airport Bus takes passengers direct from the airport to Ibiza town where connections can be made to surrounding areas. Taxis, rental cars and scooters are also available. Although mainly a tourist island with some seasonal service, Ibiza Airport hosts over 5 million passengers each year. Served by over 50 airlines, the airport has one two-level passenger terminal with departures on the ground level and first level while all arrivals are on the ground level.

Sacramento International Airport (airport code SMF) is located 10 miles northwest of downtown Sacramento, California. Serving as the gateway to Northern California, the airport is centrally located between Napa Valley, Yosemite National Park and Lake Tahoe. Handling over 4 million passengers annually, Sacramento Airport has two terminals, Terminal A and the recently upgraded Terminal B. The airport has twelve airlines that provide non-stop service to 30 destinations around the US, including Maui and Honolulu, Hawaii and internationally to Guadalajara, Mexico. Rental cars, taxis, and shuttles provide transportation. Yolobus bus also has a connection between the airport and downtown while the city is planning a light rail connection in the future.

Lanzarote Airport (airport code ACE) is located on the island of Lanzarote, the 4th largest of the Canary Islands and the closest to Africa. Located 5 kilometers from the capital of Arrecife, the airport is the 10th busiest airport in Spain with over 4.9 million passengers annually. The airport has added a second terminal building specifically designed to handle national and inter-island flights. The new terminal features a mural by island artist Cesar Manrique that was rescued from the old building. Taxis, buses and rental cars are available for transportation around the island. The airport has over 40 airlines with non-stop service throughout Spain and the rest of Europe.

Toronto's Lester B. Pearson International Airport (airport code YYZ) is leading the way for environmental management for the 21st Century. Pearson is the first North American airport to achieve ISO certification for Environmental Management and opened their first LEED® Certified building in 2007. Only 16 miles from downtown Toronto, Pearson is Canada's largest and busiest airport serving 32 million passengers annually. Named for a former Prime Minister, Pearson has two terminals, Terminal 1 with international service and Terminal 3, which has indoor access to the Sheraton Gateway Hotel connected directly to the airport. The Toronto Transit Commission's 192 Airport Rocket shuttle provides all-day bus service between downtown Toronto and the airport. Toronto's Direct Energy Centre is North America's third largest exhibition space at over 1 million square feet. Toronto is the sight of the 2015 Pan Am Games, which are expected to bring more than 250,000 visitors to the area.

Las Américas International Airport (airport code SDQ) is located near Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic, which is part of Hispaniola Island in the Caribbean. Overseeing 3.4 million passengers each year, the airport has a three-level terminal complex. Level 1 is for arrivals, Level 2 is for departures and is divided in to Terminal A (South) and the newly built Terminal B (North). Level 3 contains a food court and offices. Taxis, buses and hotel shuttles provide transportation. Twenty-four airlines serve the airport with flights from North and South America and Europe. After the 2010 Haitian earthquake, Las Américas could accommodate the Antonov An-225 aircraft, the world's heaviest, providing needed relief supplies.

Dayton International Airport (airport code DAY) is located 9 miles north of downtown Dayton, Ohio. The 3rd busiest airport in Ohio and with over 1 million passengers per year is one of the ten fastest growing airports in the US. Dayton Airport has two concourses, B and C. Situated at the crossroads of I-70 and I-75, rental cars, taxis and shuttles vans are all available. Dayton Airport is a 90-minute flight from 55 percent of the US population. With seven airlines serving 18 non-stop destinations, Dayton Airport is considered the birthplace of aviation when the Wright Brothers flew the first manned flying machine outside of Dayton on December 17, 1903.

Adelaide International Airport (airport code ADL) is located 8 kilometers west of the South Australian capital city. The 5th busiest airport in Australia, Adelaide has one terminal, Terminal 1, which reopened in 2005 after major renovations. The terminal is divided into three levels and hosts over 7 million passengers each year. Rental cars and taxis provide transport between the airport and the city. Skylink provides service between the airport and the major hotels and rail and bus stations. Over 10 airlines serve the airport with flights covering Australia and Asia. In 2007, the airport was rated "World's 2nd Best Airport" in the 5-15 million passengers category by Airport Council International.

Madrid-Barajas Airport (airport code MAD) is an international bridge connecting Europe and Central and South America. Madrid has four terminals with Terminals 1, 2 and 3 serving Spanish carriers and members of Star Alliance and Skyteam while Terminal 4 services Iberia Airlines and international carriers. Only 15 kilometers from the city center, passengers can get to Madrid by taking Metro Line 8 (pink on the metro map), which departs from Terminals 2 and 4. The airport is operated by Aena Aeropuertos, which also operates 47 other airports in Spain. A mixture of ancient and modern, Madrid is half bustling metropolis of six million people with modern skyscrapers and half quintessential village with narrow streets and sidewalk cafes. To show off the city's culture, Madrid Airport also houses permanent and revolving collections of artwork. Continuing their environmental commitments, Madrid-Barajas Airport constantly reviews sustainability practices and has had ISO certification since 2000.

Dubai International Airport (airport code DXB) is a thoroughly modern facility although it has been in existence since 1959. Today it is top five in the world for international passengers and cargo traffic. Dubai has three terminals, including the award-winning Emirates Terminal 3, which opened in 2008. Terminal 3 is the world's largest building by floor space at 1.5 million square meters and is exclusive to Emirates Airline. Dubai International Hotel, a five-star hotel owned by Dubai Airports, is located in the Sheikh Rashid Terminal of Terminal 1 and Concourse 2 of Terminal 3. Dubai Airport also runs three of the world's longest commercial flights to the US cities of Los Angeles, San Francisco and Houston. A city that began a small agricultural village is now the current home to the world's tallest building, Burj Khalifa, and Ski Dubai, a 22,500 square meter indoor ski resort with 6,000 tons of artificial snow.

Copenhagen Airport (airport code CPH) is located 8 kilometers southeast of Copenhagen, Denmark, in the township of Kastrup. Scandinavia's main airport, Copenhagen is Europe's 15th busiest airport transporting 21.5 million passengers each year. Air-rail trains link the airport with the Central Railway Station in downtown Copenhagen. Buses and rental cars are also available. Copenhagen Airport has four terminals, Terminal 1 for domestic, Terminals 2 and 3 for international and CPH Go for low-cost carriers. A new Terminal 4 is being planned. The airport features the CPH Apartment lounge that is available for all airport passengers regardless of airline. It features free WiFi, hot and cold drinks, snacks and printing facilities.

Moscow Domodedovo Airport (airport code DME) is located about 22 kilometers southeast of Moscow, Russia, and is the country's largest and busiest airport with over 22 million passengers each year. Connected to Moscow by a modern expressway, buses, taxis and rental cars can all provide transportation. Aeroexpress also has direct train service to the central Paveletsky Railway Station. Russia's first ISO certified environmentally friendly airport, 77 air carriers provide service to 36 international and 29 domestic destinations. The airport consists of a two-level terminal building with international and domestic piers and is currently undergoing expansion scheduled for completion in 2012. Domodedovo Airhotel is located 500 meters from the Passenger Terminal.

Juan Gualberto Gómez Airport (airport code VRA) is located 20 kilometers from the town of Varadero, Cuba, on the coast of the Straits of Florida south of the Florida Keys. Varadero is about 140 kilometers east from the capital of Havana. Gómez Airport has 25 airlines with flights throughout the Caribbean and between Europe, Canada and South America. Close to the beach resorts of northwestern Cuba, taxis, buses, and rental cars are available for travelers. The airport has a single terminal with three jet bridges, however, air stairs are used for some aircraft. With 20 kilometers of white sand beaches, the Playa Azul of Varadero is a large tourist area.

Bengaluru International Airport (airport code BLR) is located near the city of Bangalore in Southern India. The airport is 4 kilometers from Devanahalli and 40 kilometers from central Bangalore. The 4th busiest airport in India, Bengaluru sees between 10 and 11 million passengers each year. The airport consists of one four-level terminal. Conveniently located off National Highway 7, the airport is accessed by taxi, car rental or bus service. Twenty-eight airlines provide service to across Europe and Asia. One of the world's newest airports, Bengaluru was opened in 2008 and is India's first public-private construction project. A high-speed rail link has been proposed and is expected to begin construction shortly.
alternative name Kompong Som.

Gerald R. Ford International Airport (airport code GRR) is located southeast of Grand Rapids, Michigan, and is about 160 miles west of Detroit. Eight airlines serve the airport with 120 daily non-stop flights to 24 destinations. The airport hosts over 2 million passengers per year. In 1999, the airport was renamed for the 38th US President. Ford Airport has one terminal with two concourses, A and B. Taxis, hotel shuttles, limousines and rental cars provide transport along with The Rapid Route 17 public bus. Ford Airport has a variety of meeting rooms available including the International Room with a classroom "U" shape, projection screen, and theater that seats 50 people.

Hurghada International Airport (airport code HRG) in Egypt is located 5 kilometers southwest of downtown Hurghada and a short drive from the coastal resorts of the northern Red Sea. The airport has one recently refurbished terminal that sees 7.5 million passengers each year. Taxis and rental cars are the best ways to get to and from the airport and into the resort areas.  Part of the Egyptian Airports Company, which operates 19 airports in Egypt, Hurghada Airport  has direct flights to most European capitals and most major Russian cities on over 40 air carriers and charter companies. Once a small fishing village, Hurghada is now a bustling resort city.
